# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eugene-michael-gluhareff
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The **Apollo program**, also known as **Project Apollo**, was the United States human spaceflight program led by NASA, which landed the first humans on the Moon in 1969.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo was conceived in 1960 in the Dwight D.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Eisenhower presidency during Project Mercury and executed after Project Gemini.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo was later dedicated to President John F.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy's national goal, "before this decade is out, of landing a man on the Moon and returning him safely to the Earth" in his address to the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Approximately 650 million people worldwide watched this first landing on television.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Five subsequent Apollo missions also landed astronauts on the Moon, the last, Apollo 17, in December 1972.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In these six spaceflights, twelve people walked on the Moon.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo ran from 1961 to 1972, with the first crewed flight in 1968.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It encountered a major setback in 1967 when the Apollo 1 cabin fire killed the entire crew during a prelaunch test.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] After the first Moon landing, sufficient flight hardware remained for nine follow-on landings with a plan for extended lunar geological and astrophysical exploration.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Budget cuts forced the cancellation of three of these.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Five of the remaining six missions achieved landings; but the Apollo 13 landing had to be aborted after an oxygen tank exploded en route to the Moon, crippling the CSM.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The crew barely managed a safe return to Earth by using the Lunar Module as a "lifeboat" on the return journey.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo set several major human spaceflight milestones.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It stands alone in sending humans to the lunar surface.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo 8 was the first crewed mission to leave low Earth orbit and to orbit another celestial body, and Apollo 11 was the first crewed mission to land humans on one.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Overall, the Apollo program returned 842 pounds (382 kg) of lunar rocks to Earth, greatly contributing to the understanding of the Moon's composition and geological history.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The program laid the foundation for NASA's subsequent human spaceflight capability and funded construction of its Johnson Space Center and Kennedy Space Center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Apollo also spurred advances in many areas of technology incidental to rocketry and human spaceflight, including avionics, telecommunications, and computers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Following the end of the Apollo program, humans would not leave low Earth orbit until the Artemis II flyby of the Moon in 2026, as part of the Artemis program, established as a successor to Apollo in 2017.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Artemis intends to return humans to the Moon's surface no earlier than 2028.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The context of this was that the program focused at its beginning mainly on developing an advanced crewed spacecraft, the Apollo command and service module, succeeding the Mercury program.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A lunar landing became the focus of the program only in 1961.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Thereafter Project Gemini instead followed the Mercury program to test and study advanced crewed spaceflight technology.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo program was conceived during the Eisenhower administration in early 1960, as a follow-up to Project Mercury.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] While the Mercury capsule could support only one astronaut on a limited Earth orbital mission, Apollo would carry three.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Possible missions included ferrying crews to a space station, circumlunar flights, and eventual crewed lunar landings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In July 1960, NASA Deputy Administrator Hugh L.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Dryden announced the Apollo program to industry representatives at a series of Space Task Group conferences.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Preliminary specifications were laid out for a spacecraft with a *mission module* cabin separate from the *command module* (piloting and reentry cabin), and a *propulsion and equipment module*.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On August 30, a feasibility study competition was announced, and on October 25, three study contracts were awarded to General Dynamics/Convair, General Electric, and the Glenn L.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Meanwhile, NASA performed its own in-house spacecraft design studies led by Maxime Faget, to serve as a gauge to judge and monitor the three industry designs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy was elected president after a campaign that promised American superiority over the Soviet Union in the fields of space exploration and missile defense.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Up to the election of 1960, Kennedy had been speaking out against the "missile gap" that he and many other senators said had developed between the Soviet Union and the United States due to the inaction of President Eisenhower.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Beyond military power, Kennedy used aerospace technology as a symbol of national prestige, pledging to make the US not "first but, first and, first if, but first period".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Despite Kennedy's rhetoric, he did not immediately come to a decision on the status of the Apollo program once he became president.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] He knew little about the technical details of the space program, and was put off by the massive financial commitment required by a crewed Moon landing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] When Kennedy's newly appointed NASA Administrator James E.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Webb requested a 30 percent budget increase for his agency, Kennedy supported an acceleration of NASA's large booster program but deferred a decision on the broader issue.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On April 12, 1961, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first person to fly in space, reinforcing American fears about being left behind in a technological competition with the Soviet Union.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] At a meeting of the US House Committee on Science and Astronautics one day after Gagarin's flight, many congressmen pledged their support for a crash program aimed at ensuring that America would catch up.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy was circumspect in his response to the news, refusing to make a commitment on America's response to the Soviets.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On April 20, Kennedy sent a memo to Vice President Lyndon B.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Johnson, asking Johnson to look into the status of America's space program, and into programs that could offer NASA the opportunity to catch up.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] At the time of Kennedy's proposal, only one American had flown in space—less than a month earlier—and NASA had not yet sent an astronaut into orbit.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Even some NASA employees doubted whether Kennedy's ambitious goal could be met.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] By 1963, Kennedy even came close to agreeing to a joint US-USSR Moon mission, to eliminate duplication of effort.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The mission module was determined to be useful only as an extra room, and therefore unnecessary.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] They used Faget's design as the specification for another competition for spacecraft procurement bids in October 1961.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On November 28, 1961, North American Aviation won the contract, although its bid was not rated as good as the Martin proposal.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Webb, Dryden and Robert Seamans chose it in preference due to North American's longer association with NASA and its predecessor.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Landing humans on the Moon by the end of 1969 required the most sudden burst of technological creativity, and the largest commitment of resources ($25 billion; $187 billion in 2024 US dollars) ever made by any nation in peacetime.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] At its peak, the Apollo program employed 400,000 people and required the support of over 20,000 industrial firms and universities.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On July 1, 1960, NASA established the Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC) in Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] MSFC designed the heavy lift-class Saturn launch vehicles, which would be required for Apollo.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It became clear that managing the Apollo program would exceed the capabilities of Robert R.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Gilruth's Space Task Group, which had been directing the nation's crewed space program from NASA's Langley Research Center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] So Gilruth was given authority to grow his organization into a new NASA center, the Manned Spacecraft Center (MSC).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A site was chosen in Houston, Texas, on land donated by Rice University, and Administrator Webb announced the conversion on September 19, 1961.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It was also clear NASA would soon outgrow its practice of controlling missions from its Cape Canaveral Air Force Station launch facilities in Florida, so a new Mission Control Center would be included in the MSC.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The MSC was completed in September 1963.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It was renamed by the United States Congress in honor of Lyndon B.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It also became clear that Apollo would outgrow the Canaveral launch facilities in Florida.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The two newest launch complexes were already being built for the Saturn I and IB rockets at the northernmost end: LC-34 and LC-37.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] An even bigger facility was needed for the mammoth rocket required for the crewed lunar mission, so land acquisition was started in July 1961 for a Launch Operations Center (LOC) immediately north of Canaveral at Merritt Island.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The design, development and construction of the center was conducted by Kurt H.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Debus, a member of Wernher von Braun's original V-2 rocket engineering team.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Debus was named the LOC's first Director.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Following Kennedy's death, President Johnson issued an executive order on November 29, 1963, to rename the LOC and Cape Canaveral in honor of Kennedy.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Although at least three pads were planned, only two, designated A and B, were completed in October 1965.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The LOC also included an Operations and Checkout Building (OCB) to which Gemini and Apollo spacecraft were initially received prior to being mated to their launch vehicles.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo spacecraft could be tested in two vacuum chambers capable of simulating atmospheric pressure at altitudes up to 250,000 feet (76 km), which is nearly a vacuum.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Administrator Webb realized that in order to keep Apollo costs under control, he had to develop greater project management skills in his organization, so he recruited George E.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Mueller accepted, on the condition that he have a say in NASA reorganization necessary to effectively administer Apollo.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Webb then worked with Associate Administrator (later Deputy Administrator) Seamans to reorganize the Office of Manned Space Flight (OMSF).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On July 23, 1963, Webb announced Mueller's appointment as Deputy Associate Administrator for Manned Space Flight, to replace then Associate Administrator D.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Brainerd Holmes on his retirement effective September 1.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Under Webb's reorganization, the directors of the Manned Spacecraft Center (Gilruth), Marshall Space Flight Center (von Braun), and the Launch Operations Center (Debus) reported to Mueller.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Based on his industry experience on Air Force missile projects, Mueller realized some skilled managers could be found among high-ranking officers in the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Air Force, so he got Webb's permission to recruit General Samuel C.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Phillips, who gained a reputation for his effective management of the Minuteman program, as OMSF program controller.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Schriever agreed to loan Phillips to NASA, along with a staff of officers under him, on the condition that Phillips be made Apollo Program Director.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Mueller agreed, and Phillips managed Apollo from January 1964, until it achieved the first human landing in July 1969, after which he returned to Air Force duty.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Charles Fishman, in *One Giant Leap*, estimated the number of people and organizations involved into the Apollo program as "410,000 men and women at some 20,000 different companies contributed to the effort".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Once Kennedy had defined a goal, the Apollo mission planners were faced with the challenge of designing a spacecraft that could meet it while minimizing risk to human life, limiting cost, and not exceeding limits in possible technology and astronaut skill.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In early 1961, direct ascent was generally the mission mode in favor at NASA.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Many engineers feared that rendezvous and docking, maneuvers that had not been attempted in Earth orbit, would be nearly impossible in lunar orbit.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] LOR advocates—including Tom Dolan at Vought and John Houbolt at Langley Research Center—emphasized the important weight reductions that were offered by the LOR approach.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Throughout 1960 and 1961, Houbolt campaigned for the recognition of LOR as a viable and practical option.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Bypassing the NASA hierarchy, he sent a series of memos and reports on the issue to Associate Administrator Robert Seamans; while acknowledging that he spoke "somewhat as a voice in the wilderness", Houbolt pleaded that LOR should not be discounted in studies of the question.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Seamans's establishment of an ad hoc committee headed by his special technical assistant Nicholas E.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Golovin in July 1961, to recommend a launch vehicle to be used in the Apollo program, represented a turning point in NASA's mission mode decision.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] This committee recognized that the chosen mode was an important part of the launch vehicle choice, and recommended in favor of a hybrid EOR-LOR mode.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Its consideration of LOR—as well as Houbolt's ceaseless work—played an important role in publicizing the workability of the approach.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In late 1961 and early 1962, members of the Manned Spacecraft Center began to come around to support LOR, including the newly hired deputy director of the Office of Manned Space Flight, Joseph Shea, who became a champion of LOR.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The engineers at Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC), who were heavily invested in direct ascent, took longer to become convinced of its merits, but their conversion was announced by Wernher von Braun at a briefing on June 7, 1962.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Even after NASA reached internal agreement, it was far from smooth sailing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner kept up the pressure, even making the disagreement public during a two-day September visit by the President to Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner blurted out "No, that's no good" in front of the press, during a presentation by von Braun.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Webb jumped in and defended von Braun, until Kennedy ended the squabble by stating that the matter was "still subject to final review".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Webb held firm and issued a request for proposal to candidate Lunar Excursion Module (LEM) contractors.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner finally relented, unwilling to settle the dispute once and for all in Kennedy's office, because of the President's involvement with the October Cuban Missile Crisis, and fear of Kennedy's support for Webb.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] NASA announced the selection of Grumman as the LEM contractor in November 1962.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The LOR method had the advantage of allowing the lander spacecraft to be used as a "lifeboat" in the event of a failure of the command ship.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Some documents prove this theory was discussed before and after the method was chosen.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In 1964 an MSC study concluded, "The LM [as lifeboat] ... was finally dropped, because no single reasonable CSM failure could be identified that would prohibit use of the SPS." That type of failure happened on Apollo 13 when an oxygen tank explosion left the CSM without electrical power.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The lunar module provided propulsion, electrical power and life support to get the crew home safely.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Faget's preliminary Apollo design employed a cone-shaped command module, supported by one of several service modules providing propulsion and electrical power, sized appropriately for the space station, cislunar, and lunar landing missions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Once Kennedy's Moon landing goal became official, detailed design began of a command and service module (CSM) in which the crew would spend the entire direct-ascent mission and lift off from the lunar surface for the return trip, after being soft-landed by a larger landing propulsion module.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The command module (CM) was the conical crew cabin, designed to carry three astronauts from launch to lunar orbit and back to an Earth ocean landing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It was the only component of the Apollo spacecraft to survive without major configuration changes as the program evolved from the early Apollo study designs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Its exterior was covered with an ablative heat shield, and had its own reaction control system (RCS) engines to control its attitude and steer its atmospheric entry path.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Parachutes were carried to slow its descent to splashdown.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A cylindrical service module (SM) supported the command module, with a service propulsion engine and an RCS with propellants, and a fuel cell power generation system with liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen reactants.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A high-gain S-band antenna was used for long-distance communications on the lunar flights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] On the extended lunar missions, an orbital scientific instrument package was carried.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The service module was discarded just before reentry.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The initial lunar flight version weighed approximately 51,300 pounds (23,300 kg) fully fueled, while a later version designed to carry a lunar orbit scientific instrument package weighed just over 54,000 pounds (24,000 kg).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] North American Aviation won the contract to build the CSM, and also the second stage of the Saturn V launch vehicle for NASA.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Because the CSM design was started early before the selection of lunar orbit rendezvous, the service propulsion engine was sized to lift the CSM off the Moon, and thus was oversized to about twice the thrust required for translunar flight.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Also, there was no provision for docking with the lunar module.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A 1964 program definition study concluded that the initial design should be continued as Block I which would be used for early testing, while Block II, the actual lunar spacecraft, would incorporate the docking equipment and take advantage of the lessons learned in Block I development.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo Lunar Module (LM) was designed to descend from lunar orbit to land two astronauts on the Moon and take them back to orbit to rendezvous with the command module.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Not designed to fly through the Earth's atmosphere or return to Earth, its fuselage was designed totally without aerodynamic considerations and was of an extremely lightweight construction.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] It consisted of separate descent and ascent stages, each with its own engine.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The descent stage contained storage for the descent propellant, surface stay consumables, and surface exploration equipment.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The ascent stage contained the crew cabin, ascent propellant, and a reaction control system.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The initial LM model weighed approximately 33,300 pounds (15,100 kg), and allowed surface stays up to around 34 hours.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] An extended lunar module (ELM) weighed over 36,200 pounds (16,400 kg), and allowed surface stays of more than three days.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The contract for design and construction of the lunar module was awarded to Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation, and the project was overseen by Thomas J.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Before the Apollo program began, Wernher von Braun and his team of rocket engineers had started work on plans for very large launch vehicles, the Saturn series, and the even larger Nova series.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In the midst of these plans, von Braun was transferred from the Army to NASA and was made Director of the Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The initial direct ascent plan to send the three-person Apollo command and service module directly to the lunar surface, on top of a large descent rocket stage, would require a Nova-class launcher, with a lunar payload capability of over 180,000 pounds (82,000 kg).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The June 11, 1962, decision to use lunar orbit rendezvous enabled the Saturn V to replace the Nova, and the MSFC proceeded to develop the Saturn rocket family for Apollo.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] This was changed by the time human flights began.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Since Apollo, like Mercury, would require a launch escape system (LES) in case of a launch failure, a relatively small rocket was required for qualification flight testing of this system.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A rocket bigger than the Little Joe used by Mercury would be required, so the Little Joe II was built by General Dynamics/Convair.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] After an August 1963 qualification test flight, four LES test flights (A-001 through 004) were made at the White Sands Missile Range between May 1964 and January 1966.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Saturn I, the first US heavy lift launch vehicle, was initially planned to launch partially equipped CSMs in low Earth orbit tests.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The S-I first stage burned RP-1 with liquid oxygen (LOX) oxidizer in eight clustered Rocketdyne H-1 engines, to produce 1,500,000 pounds-force (6,670 kN) of thrust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The S-IV second stage used six liquid hydrogen-fueled Pratt & Whitney RL-10 engines with 90,000 pounds-force (400 kN) of thrust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The S-V third stage flew inactively on Saturn I four times.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The first four Saturn I test flights were launched from LC-34, with only the first stage live, carrying dummy upper stages filled with water.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The first flight with a live S-IV was launched from LC-37.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] This was followed by five launches of boilerplate CSMs (designated AS-101 through AS-105) into orbit in 1964 and 1965.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The last three of these further supported the Apollo program by also carrying Pegasus satellites, which verified the safety of the translunar environment by measuring the frequency and severity of micrometeorite impacts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In September 1962, NASA planned to launch four crewed CSM flights on the Saturn I from late 1965 through 1966, concurrent with Project Gemini.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The 22,500-pound (10,200 kg) payload capacity would have severely limited the systems which could be included, so the decision was made in October 1963 to use the uprated Saturn IB for all crewed Earth orbital flights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Saturn IB was an upgraded version of the Saturn I.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The S-IB first stage increased the thrust to 1,600,000 pounds-force (7,120 kN) by uprating the H-1 engine.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The second stage replaced the S-IV with the S-IVB-200, powered by a single J-2 engine burning liquid hydrogen fuel with LOX, to produce 200,000 pounds-force (890 kN) of thrust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] A restartable version of the S-IVB was used as the third stage of the Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Saturn IB could send over 40,000 pounds (18,100 kg) into low Earth orbit, sufficient for a partially fueled CSM or the LM.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Saturn IB launch vehicles and flights were designated with an AS-200 series number, "AS" indicating "Apollo Saturn" and the "2" indicating the second member of the Saturn rocket family.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Saturn V launch vehicles and flights were designated with an AS-500 series number, "AS" indicating "Apollo Saturn" and the "5" indicating Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The three-stage Saturn V was designed to send a fully fueled CSM and LM to the Moon.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Its capability grew to 103,600 pounds (47,000 kg) for the later advanced lunar landings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The S-IC first stage burned RP-1/LOX for a rated thrust of 7,500,000 pounds-force (33,400 kN), which was upgraded to 7,610,000 pounds-force (33,900 kN).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The second and third stages burned liquid hydrogen; the third stage was a modified version of the S-IVB, with thrust increased to 230,000 pounds-force (1,020 kN) and capability to restart the engine for translunar injection after reaching a parking orbit.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] NASA's director of flight crew operations during the Apollo program was Donald K.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] "Deke" Slayton, one of the original Mercury Seven astronauts who was medically grounded in September 1962 due to a heart murmur.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Slayton was responsible for making all Gemini and Apollo crew assignments.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Thirty-two astronauts were assigned to fly missions in the Apollo program.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Twenty-four of these left Earth's orbit and flew around the Moon between December 1968 and December 1972 (three of them twice).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Half of the 24 walked on the Moon's surface, though none of them returned to it after landing once.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] One of the moonwalkers was a trained geologist.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Of the 32, Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger Chaffee were killed during a ground test in preparation for the Apollo 1 mission.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo astronauts were chosen from the Project Mercury and Gemini veterans, plus from two later astronaut groups.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] All missions were commanded by Gemini or Mercury veterans.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Crews on all development flights (except the Earth orbit CSM development flights) through the first two landings on Apollo 11 and Apollo 12, included at least two (sometimes three) Gemini veterans.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Harrison Schmitt, a geologist, was the first NASA scientist astronaut to fly in space, and landed on the Moon on the last mission, Apollo 17.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Schmitt participated in the lunar geology training of all of the Apollo landing crews.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] NASA awarded all 32 of these astronauts its highest honor, the Distinguished Service Medal, given for "distinguished service, ability, or courage", and personal "contribution representing substantial progress to the NASA mission".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The medals were awarded posthumously to Grissom, White, and Chaffee in 1969, then to the crews of all missions from Apollo 8 onward.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] The crew that flew the first Earth orbital test mission Apollo 7, Walter M.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] Schirra, Donn Eisele, and Walter Cunningham, were awarded the lesser NASA Exceptional Service Medal, because of discipline problems with the flight director's orders during their flight.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] In October 2008, the NASA Administrator decided to award them the Distinguished Service Medals.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p01] For Schirra and Eisele, this was posthumously.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Two Block I CSMs were launched from LC-34 on suborbital flights in 1966 with the Saturn IB.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The first, AS-201 launched on February 26, reached an altitude of 265.7 nautical miles (492.1 km) and splashed down 4,577 nautical miles (8,477 km) downrange in the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The second, AS-202 on August 25, reached 617.1 nautical miles (1,142.9 km) altitude and was recovered 13,900 nautical miles (25,700 km) downrange in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] These flights validated the service module engine and the command module heat shield.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] A third Saturn IB test, AS-203 launched from pad 37, went into orbit to support design of the S-IVB upper stage restart capability needed for the Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] It carried a nose cone instead of the Apollo spacecraft, and its payload was the unburned liquid hydrogen fuel, the behavior of which engineers measured with temperature and pressure sensors, and a TV camera.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] This flight occurred on July 5, before AS-202, which was delayed because of problems getting the Apollo spacecraft ready for flight.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Two crewed orbital Block I CSM missions were planned: AS-204 and AS-205.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Block I crew positions were titled Command Pilot, Senior Pilot, and Pilot.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Senior Pilot would assume navigation duties, while the Pilot would function as a systems engineer.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts would wear a modified version of the Gemini spacesuit.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] After an uncrewed LM test flight AS-206, a crew would fly the first Block II CSM and LM in a dual mission known as AS-207/208, or AS-278 (each spacecraft would be launched on a separate Saturn IB).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Block II crew positions were titled Commander, Command Module Pilot, and Lunar Module Pilot.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts would begin wearing a new Apollo A6L spacesuit, designed to accommodate lunar extravehicular activity (EVA).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The traditional visor helmet was replaced with a clear "fishbowl" type for greater visibility, and the lunar surface EVA suit would include a water-cooled undergarment.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Deke Slayton, the grounded Mercury astronaut who became director of flight crew operations for the Gemini and Apollo programs, selected the first Apollo crew in January 1966, with Grissom as Command Pilot, White as Senior Pilot, and rookie Donn F.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] But Eisele dislocated his shoulder twice aboard the KC135 weightlessness training aircraft, and had to undergo surgery on January 27.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA announced the final crew selection for AS-204 on March 21, 1966, with the backup crew consisting of Gemini veterans James McDivitt and David Scott, with rookie Russell L.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Mercury/Gemini veteran Wally Schirra, Eisele, and rookie Walter Cunningham were announced on September 29 as the prime crew for AS-205.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In December 1966, the AS-205 mission was canceled, since the validation of the CSM would be accomplished on the 14-day first flight, and AS-205 would have been devoted to space experiments and contribute no new engineering knowledge about the spacecraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Its Saturn IB was allocated to the dual mission, now redesignated AS-205/208 or AS-258, planned for August 1967.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] McDivitt, Scott and Schweickart were promoted to the prime AS-258 crew, and Schirra, Eisele and Cunningham were reassigned as the Apollo 1 backup crew.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Eventually, the planned AS-204 flight date was pushed to February 21, 1967.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] North American Aviation was prime contractor not only for the Apollo CSM, but for the Saturn V S-II second stage as well, and delays in this stage pushed the first uncrewed Saturn V flight AS-501 from late 1966 to November 1967.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The problems with North American were severe enough in late 1965 to cause Manned Space Flight Administrator George Mueller to appoint program director Samuel Phillips to head a "tiger team" to investigate North American's problems and identify corrections.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Phillips documented his findings in a December 19 letter to NAA president Lee Atwood, with a strongly worded letter by Mueller, and also gave a presentation of the results to Mueller and Deputy Administrator Robert Seamans.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Meanwhile, Grumman was also encountering problems with the Lunar Module, eliminating hopes it would be ready for crewed flight in 1967, not long after the first crewed CSM flights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Grissom, White, and Chaffee decided to name their flight Apollo 1 as a motivational focus on the first crewed flight.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] They trained and conducted tests of their spacecraft at North American, and in the altitude chamber at the Kennedy Space Center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] A "plugs-out" test was planned for January, which would simulate a launch countdown on LC-34 with the spacecraft transferring from pad-supplied to internal power.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] If successful, this would be followed by a more rigorous countdown simulation test closer to the February 21 launch, with both spacecraft and launch vehicle fueled.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The plugs-out test began on the morning of January 27, 1967, and immediately was plagued with problems.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] First, the crew noticed a strange odor in their spacesuits which delayed the sealing of the hatch.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Then, communications problems frustrated the astronauts and forced a hold in the simulated countdown.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] During this hold, an electrical fire began in the cabin and spread quickly in the high pressure, 100% oxygen atmosphere.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Pressure rose high enough from the fire that the cabin inner wall burst, allowing the fire to erupt onto the pad area and frustrating attempts to rescue the crew.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts were asphyxiated before the hatch could be opened.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA immediately convened an accident review board, overseen by both houses of Congress.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] While the determination of responsibility for the accident was complex, the review board concluded that "deficiencies existed in command module design, workmanship and quality control".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] At the insistence of NASA Administrator Webb, North American removed Harrison Storms as command module program manager.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Webb also reassigned Apollo Spacecraft Program Office (ASPO) Manager Joseph Francis Shea, replacing him with George Low.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] To remedy the causes of the fire, changes were made in the Block II spacecraft and operational procedures, the most important of which were use of a nitrogen/oxygen mixture instead of pure oxygen before and during launch, and removal of flammable cabin and space suit materials.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Block II design already called for replacement of the Block I plug-type hatch cover with a quick-release, outward opening door.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA discontinued the crewed Block I program, using the Block I spacecraft only for uncrewed Saturn V flights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Crew members would also exclusively wear modified, fire-resistant A7L Block II space suits, and would be designated by the Block II titles, regardless of whether a LM was present on the flight or not.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] On April 24, 1967, Mueller published an official Apollo mission numbering scheme, using sequential numbers for all flights, crewed or uncrewed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The sequence would start with Apollo 4 to cover the first three uncrewed flights while retiring the Apollo 1 designation to honor the crew, per their widows' wishes.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In September 1967, Mueller approved a sequence of mission types which had to be accomplished in order to achieve the crewed lunar landing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Each step had to be accomplished before the next ones could be performed, and it was unknown how many tries of each mission would be necessary; therefore letters were used instead of numbers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The list of types covered follow-on lunar exploration to include **H** lunar landings, **I** for lunar orbital survey missions, and **J** for extended-stay lunar landings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The delay in the CSM caused by the fire enabled NASA to catch up on human-rating the LM and Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 4 (AS-501) was the first uncrewed flight of the Saturn V, carrying a Block I CSM on November 9, 1967.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The capability of the command module's heat shield to survive a trans-lunar reentry was demonstrated by using the service module engine to ram it into the atmosphere at higher than the usual Earth-orbital reentry speed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 5 (AS-204) was the first uncrewed test flight of the LM in Earth orbit, launched from pad 37 on January 22, 1968, by the Saturn IB that would have been used for Apollo 1.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The LM engines were successfully test-fired and restarted, despite a computer programming error, which cut short the first descent stage firing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The ascent engine was fired in abort mode, known as a "fire-in-the-hole" test, where it was lit simultaneously with jettison of the descent stage.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Although Grumman wanted a second uncrewed test, George Low decided the next LM flight would be crewed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] This was followed on April 4, 1968, by Apollo 6 (AS-502) which carried a CSM and a LM Test Article as ballast.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The intent of this mission was to achieve trans-lunar injection, followed closely by a simulated direct-return abort, using the service module engine to achieve another high-speed reentry.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Saturn V experienced pogo oscillation, a problem caused by non-steady engine combustion, which damaged fuel lines in the second and third stages.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Two S-II engines shut down prematurely, but the remaining engines were able to compensate.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The damage to the third stage engine was more severe, preventing it from restarting for trans-lunar injection.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Mission controllers were able to use the service module engine to essentially repeat the flight profile of Apollo 4.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Based on the good performance of Apollo 6 and identification of satisfactory fixes to the Apollo 6 problems, NASA declared the Saturn V ready to fly crew, canceling a third uncrewed test.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 7, launched from LC-34 on October 11, 1968, was the C mission, crewed by Schirra, Eisele, and Cunningham.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] It was an 11-day Earth-orbital flight which tested the CSM systems.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 8 was planned to be the D mission in December 1968, crewed by McDivitt, Scott and Schweickart, launched on a Saturn V instead of two Saturn IBs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In the summer it had become clear that the LM would not be ready in time.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Rather than waste the Saturn V on another simple Earth-orbiting mission, ASPO Manager George Low suggested the bold step of sending Apollo 8 to orbit the Moon instead, deferring the D mission to the next mission in March 1969, and eliminating the E mission.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Soviet Union had sent two tortoises, mealworms, wine flies, and other lifeforms around the Moon on September 15, 1968, aboard Zond 5, and it was believed they might soon repeat the feat with human cosmonauts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The decision was not announced publicly until completion of Apollo 7.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Gemini veterans Frank Borman and Jim Lovell, and rookie William Anders captured the world's attention by making ten lunar orbits in 20 hours, transmitting television pictures of the lunar surface on Christmas Eve, and returning safely to Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The following March, LM flight, rendezvous and docking were demonstrated in Earth orbit on Apollo 9, and Schweickart tested the full lunar EVA suit with its portable life support system (PLSS) outside the LM.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The F mission was carried out on Apollo 10 in May 1969 by Gemini veterans Thomas P.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Stafford and Cernan took the LM to within 50,000 feet (15 km) of the lunar surface.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The G mission was achieved on Apollo 11 in July 1969 by an all-Gemini veteran crew consisting of Neil Armstrong, Michael Collins and Buzz Aldrin.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Armstrong and Aldrin performed the first landing at the Sea of Tranquility at 20:17:40 UTC on July 20, 1969.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts returned safely on July 24.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Bean made a precision landing of Apollo 12 within walking distance of the Surveyor 3 uncrewed lunar probe, which had landed in April 1967 on the Ocean of Storms.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The command module pilot was Gemini veteran Richard F.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Conrad and Bean carried the first lunar surface color television camera, but it was damaged when accidentally pointed into the Sun.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] They made two EVAs totaling 7 hours and 45 minutes.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] On one, they walked to the Surveyor, photographed it, and removed some parts which they returned to Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The contracted batch of 15 Saturn Vs was enough for lunar landing missions through Apollo 20.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Shortly after Apollo 11, NASA publicized a preliminary list of eight more planned landing sites after Apollo 12, with plans to increase the mass of the CSM and LM for the last five missions, along with the payload capacity of the Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] These final missions would combine the I and J types in the 1967 list, allowing the CMP to operate a package of lunar orbital sensors and cameras while his companions were on the surface, and allowing them to stay on the Moon for over three days.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] These missions would also carry the Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) increasing the exploration area and allowing televised liftoff of the LM.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Also, the Block II spacesuit was revised for the extended missions to allow greater flexibility and visibility for driving the LRV.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The success of the first two landings allowed the remaining missions to be crewed with a single veteran as commander, with two rookies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 13 launched Lovell, Jack Swigert, and Fred Haise in April 1970, headed for the Fra Mauro formation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] But two days out, a liquid oxygen tank exploded, disabling the service module and forcing the crew to use the LM as a "lifeboat" to return to Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Another NASA review board was convened to determine the cause, which turned out to be a combination of damage of the tank in the factory, and a subcontractor not making a tank component according to updated design specifications.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo was grounded again, for the remainder of 1970 while the oxygen tank was redesigned and an extra one was added.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] About the time of the first landing in 1969, it was decided to use an existing Saturn V to launch the Skylab orbital laboratory pre-built on the ground, replacing the original plan to construct it in orbit from several Saturn IB launches; this eliminated Apollo 20.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA's yearly budget also began to shrink in light of the landing, and NASA also had to make funds available for the development of the upcoming Space Shuttle.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] By 1971, the decision was made to also cancel missions 18 and 19.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The two unused Saturn Vs became museum exhibits at the John F.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Kennedy Space Center on Merritt Island, Florida, George C.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Marshall Space Center in Huntsville, Alabama, Michoud Assembly Facility in New Orleans, Louisiana, and Lyndon B.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The cutbacks forced mission planners to reassess the original planned landing sites in order to achieve the most effective geological sample and data collection from the remaining four missions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 15 had been planned to be the last of the H series missions, but since there would be only two subsequent missions left, it was changed to the first of three J missions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 13's Fra Mauro mission was reassigned to Apollo 14, commanded in February 1971 by Mercury veteran Alan Shepard, with Stuart Roosa and Edgar Mitchell.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Shepard and Mitchell spent 33 hours and 31 minutes on the surface, and completed two EVAs totalling 9 hours 24 minutes, which was a record for the longest EVA by a lunar crew at the time.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In August 1971, just after conclusion of the Apollo 15 mission, President Richard Nixon proposed canceling the two remaining lunar landing missions, Apollo 16 and 17.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Office of Management and Budget Deputy Director Caspar Weinberger was opposed to this, and persuaded Nixon to keep the remaining missions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 15 was launched on July 26, 1971, with David Scott, Alfred Worden and James Irwin.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Scott and Irwin landed on July 30 near Hadley Rille, and spent just under two days, 19 hours on the surface.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In over 18 hours of EVA, they collected about 77 kilograms (170 lb) of lunar material.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 16 landed in the Descartes Highlands on April 20, 1972.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The crew was commanded by John Young, with Ken Mattingly and Charles Duke.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Young and Duke spent just under three days on the surface, with a total of over 20 hours EVA.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 17 was the last of the Apollo program, landing in the Taurus–Littrow region in December 1972.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Evans and NASA's first scientist-astronaut, geologist Harrison H.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Schmitt was originally scheduled for Apollo 18, but the lunar geological community lobbied for his inclusion on the final lunar landing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Cernan and Schmitt stayed on the surface for just over three days and spent just over 23 hours of total EVA.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Several missions were planned for but were canceled before details were finalized.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Source: *Apollo by the Numbers: A Statistical Reference* (Orloff 2004).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program returned over 382 kg (842 lb) of lunar rocks and soil to the Lunar Receiving Laboratory in Houston.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Today, 75% of the samples are stored at the Lunar Sample Laboratory Facility built in 1979.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The rocks collected from the Moon are extremely old compared to rocks found on Earth, as measured by radiometric dating techniques.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] They range in age from about 3.2 billion years for the basaltic samples derived from the lunar maria, to about 4.6 billion years for samples derived from the highlands crust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] As such, they represent samples from a very early period in the development of the Solar System, that are largely absent on Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] One important rock found during the Apollo Program is dubbed the Genesis Rock, retrieved by astronauts David Scott and James Irwin during the Apollo 15 mission.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] This anorthosite rock is composed almost exclusively of the calcium-rich feldspar mineral anorthite, and is believed to be representative of the highland crust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] A geochemical component called KREEP was discovered by Apollo 12, which has no known terrestrial counterpart.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] KREEP and the anorthositic samples have been used to infer that the outer portion of the Moon was once completely molten (see lunar magma ocean).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Almost all the rocks show evidence of impact process effects.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Many samples appear to be pitted with micrometeoroid impact craters, which is never seen on Earth rocks, due to the thick atmosphere.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Many show signs of being subjected to high-pressure shock waves that are generated during impact events.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Some of the returned samples are of *impact melt* (materials melted near an impact crater.) All samples returned from the Moon are highly brecciated as a result of being subjected to multiple impact events.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] From analyses of the composition of the returned lunar samples, it is now believed that the Moon was created through the impact of a large astronomical body with Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo cost $25.4 billion or approximately $257 billion (2023) using improved cost analysis.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Of this amount, $20.2 billion ($149 billion adjusted) was spent on the design, development, and production of the Saturn family of launch vehicles, the Apollo spacecraft, spacesuits, scientific experiments, and mission operations.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The cost of constructing and operating Apollo-related ground facilities, such as the NASA human spaceflight centers and the global tracking and data acquisition network, added an additional $5.2 billion ($38.3 billion adjusted).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The amount grows to $28 billion ($280 billion adjusted) if the costs for related projects such as Project Gemini and the robotic Ranger, Surveyor, and Lunar Orbiter programs are included.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Accurate estimates of human spaceflight costs were difficult in the early 1960s, as the capability was new and management experience was lacking.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Preliminary cost analysis by NASA estimated $7 billion – $12 billion for a crewed lunar landing effort.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA Administrator James Webb increased this estimate to $20 billion before reporting it to Vice President Johnson in April 1961.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Project Apollo was a massive undertaking, representing the largest research and development project in peacetime.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] At its peak, it employed over 400,000 employees and contractors around the country and accounted for more than half of NASA's total spending in the 1960s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] After the first Moon landing, public and political interest waned, including that of President Nixon, who wanted to rein in federal spending.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] NASA's budget could not sustain Apollo missions which cost, on average, $445 million ($2.73 billion adjusted) each while simultaneously developing the Space Shuttle.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The final fiscal year of Apollo funding was 1973.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Looking beyond the crewed lunar landings, NASA investigated several post-lunar applications for Apollo hardware.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo Extension Series (*Apollo X*) proposed up to 30 flights to Earth orbit, using the space in the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter (SLA) to house a small orbital laboratory (workshop).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Astronauts would continue to use the CSM as a ferry to the station.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] This study was followed by design of a larger orbital workshop to be built in orbit from an empty S-IVB Saturn upper stage and grew into the Apollo Applications Program (AAP).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The workshop was to be supplemented by the Apollo Telescope Mount, which could be attached to the ascent stage of the lunar module via a rack.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The most ambitious plan called for using an empty S-IVB as an interplanetary spacecraft for a Venus fly-by mission.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The S-IVB orbital workshop was the only one of these plans to make it off the drawing board.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Dubbed Skylab, it was assembled on the ground rather than in space, and launched in 1973 using the two lower stages of a Saturn V.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] It was equipped with an Apollo Telescope Mount.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Skylab's last crew departed the station on February 8, 1974, and the station itself re-entered the atmosphere in 1979 after development of the Space Shuttle was delayed too long to save it.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo–Soyuz program also used Apollo hardware for the first joint nation spaceflight, paving the way for future cooperation with other nations in the Space Shuttle and International Space Station programs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] In 2008, Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency's SELENE probe observed evidence of the halo surrounding the Apollo 15 Lunar Module blast crater while orbiting above the lunar surface.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Beginning in 2009, NASA's robotic Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter, while orbiting 50 kilometers (31 mi) above the Moon, photographed the remnants of the Apollo program left on the lunar surface, and each site where crewed Apollo flights landed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The flags cannot be seen through a telescope from Earth.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program has been described as the greatest technological achievement in human history.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Apollo stimulated many areas of technology, leading to over 1,800 spinoff products as of 2015, including advances in the development of cordless power tools, fireproof materials, heart monitors, solar panels, digital imaging, and the use of liquid methane as fuel.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The flight computer design used in both the lunar and command modules was, along with the Polaris and Minuteman missile systems, the driving force behind early research into integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] By 1963, Apollo was using 60 percent of the United States' production of ICs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The crucial difference between the requirements of Apollo and the missile programs was Apollo's much greater need for reliability.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] While the Navy and Air Force could work around reliability problems by deploying more missiles, the political and financial cost of failure of an Apollo mission was unacceptably high.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Technologies and techniques required for Apollo were developed by Project Gemini.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo project was enabled by NASA's adoption of new advances in semiconductor electronic technology, including metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) in the Interplanetary Monitoring Platform (IMP) and silicon integrated circuit chips in the Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The crew of Apollo 8 sent the first live televised pictures of the Earth and the Moon back to Earth, and read from the creation story in the Book of Genesis, on Christmas Eve 1968.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] An estimated one-quarter of the population of the world saw—either live or delayed—the Christmas Eve transmission during the ninth orbit of the Moon, and an estimated one-fifth of the population of the world watched the live transmission of the Apollo 11 moonwalk.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program also affected environmental activism in the 1970s due to photos taken by the astronauts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The most well known include *Earthrise*, taken by William Anders on Apollo 8, and *The Blue Marble*, taken by the Apollo 17 astronauts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] *The Blue Marble* was released during a surge in environmentalism, and became a symbol of the environmental movement as a depiction of Earth's frailty, vulnerability, and isolation amid the vast expanse of space.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] According to *The Economist*, Apollo succeeded in accomplishing President Kennedy's goal of taking on the Soviet Union in the Space Race by accomplishing a singular and significant achievement, to demonstrate the superiority of the free-market system.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] The publication noted the irony that in order to achieve the goal, the program required the organization of tremendous public resources within a vast, centralized government bureaucracy.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] Prior to Apollo 11's 40th anniversary in 2009, NASA searched for the original videotapes of the mission's live televised moonwalk.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] After an exhaustive three-year search, it was concluded that the tapes had probably been erased and reused.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/apollo-program-p02] A new digitally remastered version of the best available broadcast television footage was released instead.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe until English colonisation in the 1600s, Bridgeport was incorporated as a town in 1821 and as a city in 1836.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was a resident of the city and served as the town's mayor in 1871.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum built four houses in Bridgeport and housed his circus in town during winter.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the early 20th century, the city saw an economic and population boom, becoming by all measures Connecticut's chief manufacturing city by 1905.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was the site of the world's first mutual telephone exchange (1877), the first dental hygiene school (1949), and the first bank telephone bill service in the US (1981).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inventor Harvey Hubbell II invented the first American electric plug outlet in Bridgeport in 1912.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Frisbie Pie Company was founded and operated in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The world's first Subway restaurant opened in the city's North End in 1965.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] After World War II, industrial decline and suburbanization led to the loss of major employers and affluent residents, contributing to poverty and violent crime.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Since the early 21st century, however, the city has undertaken significant redevelopment efforts, and its crime rate fell by nearly 50 percent between 2010 and 2018.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport is home to three museums; the University of Bridgeport, Housatonic Community College, and part of Sacred Heart University; and the state's only zoo.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is officially nicknamed "Park City" due to its 35 public parks, which take up 1,300 acres.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Although none are headquartered within the city itself, more than a dozen Fortune 500 companies are based in its metropolitan area.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has been consistently ranked by various sites as among the 25 most ethnically and culturally diverse American cities.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe during the start of European colonization.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The earliest European communal settlement was in the historical Stratfield district, along US Route 1, known in colonial times as the King's Highway.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Close by, Mount Grove Cemetery was laid out on what was a native village that extended past the 1650s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is also an ancient Paugussett burial ground.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The burgeoning farming community grew and became a center of trade, shipbuilding, and whaling.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was incorporated to subsidize the Housatonic Railroad and rapidly industrialized following the rail line's connection to the New York and New Haven railroad.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was given its name because of the need for bridges over the Pequonnock River that provided a navigable port at the mouth of the river.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Manufacturing was the mainstay of the local economy until the 1970s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The first documented European settlement within the present city limits of Bridgeport took place in 1644, centered at Black Rock Harbor and along North Avenue between Park and Briarwood Avenues.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The place was called **Pequonnock** (Quiripi for "Cleared Land"), after a band of the Paugussett, an Algonquian-speaking Native American people who occupied this area.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] One of their sacred sites was Golden Hill, which overlooked the harbor and was the location of natural springs and their planting fields.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (It has since been blasted through for construction of an expressway.) The Golden Hill Indians were granted a reservation here by the Colony of Connecticut in 1639; it lasted until 1802.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (One of the tribes acquired land for a small reservation in the late 19th century that was recognized by the state.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1659, the general court in Hartford established the official borders of the Paugussett Reservation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport's early years were marked by residents' reliance on fishing and farming.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This was similar to the economy of the Paugussett, who had cultivated corn, beans, and squash; and fished and gathered shellfish from both the river and sound.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A village called **Newfield** began to develop around the corner of State and Water Streets in the 1760s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The area officially became known as **Stratfield** in 1695 or 1701, due to its location between the already existing towns of *Strat*ford and Fair*field*.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the American Revolution, Newfield Harbor was a center of privateering.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the time of the State of Connecticut's ratification of the Articles of Confederation in 1781, many of the local farmers held shares in vessels trading at Newfield Harbor or had begun trading in their own name.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Newfield initially expanded around the coasting trade with Boston, New York, and Baltimore and the international trade with the West Indies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The commercial activity of the village was clustered around the wharves on the west bank of the Pequonnock, while the churches were erected inland on Broad Street.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1787, the Fairfield County Court ordered the laying out and widening of what is now State Street and Main Street in downtown Bridgeport, along the Pequannock River then Newfield.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was assumed before the Revolution that this land would grow into a city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1800, the village became the Borough of Bridgeport, the first so incorporated in the state.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was named for the Newfield or Lottery Bridge across the Pequonnock, connecting the wharves on its east and west banks.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Bank was established in 1806.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, the township of Bridgeport became independent of Stratford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, a small community of remaining Golden Hill Pauguasett Natives, along with free blacks and runaway slaves was established in the South End along Main Street known as Little Liberia, with its own churches, schools and hotels, and served as a stop in the underground railroad.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Many remaining Paugusset Indians also lived there.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West India trade died down around 1840, but by that time the Bridgeport Steamship Company (1824) and Bridgeport Whaling Company (1833) had been incorporated and the Housatonic Railroad chartered (1836).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The HRRC ran upstate along the Housatonic Valley, connecting with Massachusetts's Berkshire Railroad at the state line.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was chartered as Connecticut's fifth city in 1836 in order to enable the town council to secure funding (ultimately $150,000) to provide to the HRRC and ensure that it would terminate in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Naugatuck Railroad—connecting Bridgeport to Waterbury and Winsted along the Naugatuck River—was chartered in 1845 and began operation four years later.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The same year, the New York and New Haven Railroad began operation, connecting Bridgeport to New York and the other towns along the north shore of the Long Island Sound.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Now a major junction, the city began to industrialize.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The city's first immigrants were Irish Catholics who settled in the Sterling Hill section of the Hollow.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Having come to the US to escape the famine, they arrived in town during the 1830s to build the railroad.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They mostly lived in wooden four to six family tenements, often subdivided homes.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum spent a night in Bridgeport, and there met Charles Stratton, a local dwarf.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] He soon became part of Barnum's act and a star under the name "General Tom Thumb".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum moved to Bridgeport and built four houses in the city over the course of his life, the first being Iranistan.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1852, Barnum began an endeavor with William Noble to develop the land (inherited by Noble) on the other side of the Pequonnock River, across the river from Bridgeport to be known as "East Bridgeport" with Washington Park at the center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The new neighborhood had homes, commerce, and factories, centered around East Main Street.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The neighborhood eventually became the East Side of Bridgeport (occasionally spelled "Eastside").
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1863, during the Civil War, the *Bridgeport Standard* ran a series of articles encouraging the creation of a public park in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum, William Noble and Nathaniel Wheeler to purchase the land on Long Island Sound and donating the land to the city in 1864.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The land on the shore became Seaside Park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A second park was built near East Main Street, when in 1878, James Beardsley donated more than 100 acres (40 ha) to the city along the Pequonnock River under the condition that the land be "kept the same forever as a public park".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Both parks were designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, known for creating Central Park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] These two large public parks gave Bridgeport the nickname "The Park City".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Augustine Cathedral was finished in 1869, built by the Irish who had arrived 30 year earlier.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Saint James Church, predating the Archdiocese of Hartford, was the first Catholic congregation in Fairfield County, starting with 250 members in 1842.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The congregation gave rise to St Augustine's in Sterling Hill, the seat of the Diocese of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Following the Civil War, the town held several iron foundries and factories manufacturing firearms, metallic cartridges, horse harnesses, locks, and blinds.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Wheeler & Wilson's sewing machines were exported throughout the world.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport absorbed the West End and the village of Black Rock and its busy harbor in 1870.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was elected mayor of the town, which afterwards served as the winter headquarters of Barnum and Bailey's Circus and Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum also helped establish Fairfield County's first hospital (Conn.'s 3rd) and the Bridgeport-Port Jefferson ferry, connecting the town to Long Island.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Harvey Hubbell founded Hubbell Incorporated in Bridgeport in 1888.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Holmes & Edwards Silver Co. was founded in 1882, its wares sold nationally, and the company became part of the International Silver Company in 1898.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (The H&E brand continued well into the 1950s and was advertised in national magazines such as *LIFE* and *Ladies' Home Journal*.) Hungarian immigrants began to arrive, which led to the Ráckόczi Hungarian Aid Association in Bridgeport in 1887 and the American Hungarian Immigrant Aid Society in 1892.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They established themselves in the West End.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1894, Bridgeport's Slavic immigrants played a major role in the development of the Orthodox Christian faith in America when they met with Fr Alexis Toth (now Saint Alexis) and founded Holy Ghost Russian Orthodox Church in the city's Eastside.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This parish became the mother church of all Orthodox Churches in New England.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] From 1870 to 1910, Bridgeport became the largest industrial center in Connecticut; its population rose from around 25,000 to over 100,000, including thousands of Irish, Slovaks, Hungarians, Germans, English, and Italian immigrants.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Jewish migration to the city began in the 1881, with an influx of Polish, Russian, and especially Hungarian Jews calling Bridgeport home.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Jew Edwin Land grew up to invent the Polaroid.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1905, Bridgeport was already "the largest industrial center in the state, $49,381,348 was invested in manufacturing and the products being valued at $44,586,519." The city was a port of entry with its imports being valued at around $656,271 in 1908.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Singer factory joined Wheeler & Wilson in producing sewing machines and the Locomobile Company of America was a prominent early automobile manufacturer, producing a prototype of the Stanley Steamer and various luxury cars.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was also the center of America's corset production, responsible for 19.9% of the national total, and became the headquarters of Remington Arms following its 1912 merger with the Union Metallic Cartridge Co.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Around the time of the First World War, Bridgeport was also producing steam-fitting and heating apparatuses, brass goods, phonographs, typewriters, milling machines, brassieres, and saddles.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Brideport's Italian immigrants settled in the "Central End", today's Little Italy, and the city was the 3rd most Italian in the state by 1910.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Their newspapers were the weekly *La Tribuna de Connecticut* (1906–1908) and later *La Sentinella* (1920–1948) The West End along Wordin Avenue, known as "Hunktown", grew into one of the largest Hungarian communities in the US.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was visited by Hungarian republicans trying to take down the Austro-Hungarian monarchy, in order to garner support.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West Side nearby was home to Slovenians, French-Canadians and Swedish immigrants.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By 1910 Bridgeport had grown into second largest city in Connecticut at 102,052, behind New Haven.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Between 1910 and 1920, during World War I, the city's population exploded from 102,054 to 143,555, due to the city's role in the First World War.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport had the largest factory in the world at the time, the new Remington Arms plant on Boston Avenue (on the East Side).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Built in 1915, it had 13 separate buildings, each of them 5 stories, connected by a long corridor half a mile long.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The purpose of the building was to fulfil a company order from the Russian tzar for a million rifles and 100 million rounds of ammunition.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The construction site was protected by the National Guard to prevent Bolshevik arson.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory by 1916 employed 16,000 people and led to the construction of "Remington City" in the Mill Hill neighborhood, and "Remington Village" in the East End, by Remington Arms.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the summer of 1915, a series of strikes imposed the eight-hour day on the town's factories; rather than moving business elsewhere, the success spread the eight-hour day throughout the Northeast.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Due to housing shortages in many US cities during World War I, the federal government created the US Housing Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This resulted in 7 USHC housing developments being built in Bridgeport, notably Seaside Village in the South End and Black Rock Gardens in Black Rock.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By this point, Remington Arms was producing 50% of America's cartridges during the war, with 17,000 employees, and homes for new workers were needed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory became a General Electric plant after the war.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The First World War had continued the city's expansion so that, on the eve of the Great Depression, there were more than 500 factories in Bridgeport, including Columbia Records' primary pressing plant and a Singer Sewing Machine factory.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The 1920s saw the city's population stabilize at 143,555 after the war.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Roaring Twenties brought more leisure and entertainment.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1919, the city of Bridgeport bought Pleaseure Beach (also known as Steepchase Island) for $220,000.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was an amusement park and beach on an island in the East End next to Stratford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1920, the city parks commissioner began the process of creating a zoo in Beardsley Park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport a stop became for performances with around 20 theatres.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 1922 was the year the elegantly designed Majestic and Poli Palace theatres, were built downtown, along with the Savoy Hotel.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Poli Palace theatre (built by Sylvester Poli) was the largest theatre in the state of Connecticut, with gilded hand-carved moldings and vaulted ceilings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1928, the city bought an 800-acre (320 ha) racetrack and landing field in Lordship to construct Bridgeport Airport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Spanish immigration in 1920 and 1921 brought hundreds of migrants from Spain, particularly from Pedreguer, Valencia, where "practically the entire town migrated" to Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the Great Depression the city elected Socialist party candidate Jasper McLevy as mayor in 1933.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] McLevy's election made headlines as a New England city had a socialist mayor.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for cutting costs, he would serve as mayor for 12 terms, finally losing in 1957.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Great Migration led southern African-Americans to Bridgeport around the 1930s (thanks to railroads) along with black foreigners (such as Cape Verdean), By 1930, Bridgeport had the third largest percentage of African Americans in New England.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Italian population by 1930 had more than doubled, now the city's largest ethnic group.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The build-up to World War II helped the city's recovery in the late 1930s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Suburban development made its expansion into the undeveloped North End neighborhood.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] On Park Avenue in 1962 the Museum of Art, Science and Industry (MASI) was opened to the public, today's Discovery Museum and Planetarium.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for the newly developed approach of hands on-exhibits, the Museum became science oriented later on.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Continued development of new suburban housing outside of Bridgeport in the city's adjacent suburbs such as Fairfield and Milford attracted middle and upper-class residents, leaving the city with a higher proportion of poor.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the 1960s, Puerto Ricans had begun to immigrate to settle to Bridgeport in large numbers, and by about 1970 had made up 10% of the city's population, or 15,000 people, the largest Puerto Rican population in Connecticut, and they would continue to grow.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Groups such as the local Young Lords branch organized themselves on East Main Street, leading to activism to advance the Puerto Rican community with increased access to health care, better housing, food and an end to poverty and police brutality.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As cities across the country were renovating their central business district after the war, Bridgeport attempted its own urban renewal projects in its old downtown in the early 1960s during the construction of the highways.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hunktown, with a population of 15,000 and the Irish neighborhood in the South End were demolished and replaced with highways and an industrial park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Trumbull Shopping Park was built just outside Bridgeport city limits in Trumbull in 1965, Connecticut's first fully enclosed shopping mall.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport under Mayor Tedesco went under the 52-acre (21 ha) State Street redevelopment project, demolishing 52 acres of State Street, clearing the land for development.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Replaced with modern high-rise office buildings, parking, the Route 8/25 expressway towards Waterbury and Newtown, and a shopping mall at its core.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Large parts of Main Street were demolished in what was called the Congress Street Renewal project, nothing was built on the land.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Constructed with federal funding, on Lafayette Boulevard and Broad Street, the 450,000 acre, 2 story (with basement) Lafayette Shopping Plaza was erected, a downtown shopping mall with a Sears and a Gimbels department store as anchors connected to it.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Military contracts during the 1950s and 1960s enabled the Bridgeport-Lycoming division of AVCO, founded 1951, to employ at times more than 12,000 people, building tanks, helicopters, and other military hardware.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Decreased demand led to layoffs, and then closure in 1984.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other examples of urban development include two city landmarks, the 12-story 855 Main Street (People's Savings Bank building), and 18-floor Park City Plaza, (State National Bank building) built 1972.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The plan for three identical towers never materialized, due to the Oil Crisis and corporate vacancies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As such, most skyscraper construction models for downtown Bridgeport from the 70s were never built, unlike Hartford (a city already home to major insurance companies) or Stamford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Much of north downtown Bridgeport would end up abandoned, neglected and boarded up as department and discount stores closed, leaving only federal and municipal buildings along now empty lots.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Restructuring of heavy industry starting after the mid-20th century caused the loss of thousands of jobs and residents.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like other urban centers in Connecticut, Bridgeport suffered during the deindustrialization of the United States in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was sold 5 years after a rollercoaster caught fire.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The old Bridgeport station caught fire in 1978.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In September 1978, Bridgeport teachers went on a 19-day strike due to deadlocked contract negotiations.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A court order, as well as a state law that made strikes by public workers illegal in Connecticut, resulted in 274 teachers being arrested and jailed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In November 1978, a wave of arson passed through the city's East side, with the fire chief calling it as a microcosm of "the Bronx".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The city suffered from overall mismanagement, for which several city officials were convicted, contributing to the economic and social decline.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The once busy Lafayette Shopping Plaza began to lose customers after Gimbel's closed in 1984.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Replaced with a Read's store, the mall was later bought by Hi-Ho Industries and renamed "Hi-Ho Mall", until it closed in 1993 and became Housatonic Community College in 1997.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] That's economic power, right?" In 1985, Bridgeport was still Connecticut's chief manufacturing center, its major industries including General Electric, Remington Shaver, Bryant Electric, and Raybestos plants.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A *New York Times* in 1985 stated Bridgeport was the fifth largest banking center in New England, with five of the banks based Bridgeport having assets of more than $6 billion.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest scissors, shear and surgical materials manufacturer in the world by 1946, Bridgeport-based ACME Shear closed its Bridgeport plant in 1996 due to mergers and acquisitions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The industrial operations relocated to Fremont, North Carolina.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Between 1984 and 1989 the construction of the new $75 million headquarters for People's United Bank, the second largest bank in New England.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport in 1989 had more homicides per capita than any Northeastern US city over 100,000 people.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport had a smaller police force than smaller cities like Hartford or New Haven, yet hiring due to city financial issues, having not recovered from the exodus of manufacturing companies, would result in even higher taxes for residents.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1991, the city filed for bankruptcy protection but was declared solvent by a federal court.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Moran lost the election to Joseph Ganim, at 33 years old, the youngest person to hold that office. and under him the city was able to begin redevelopment with the construction of the Arena at Harbor Yard and the Ballpark at Harbor Yard.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport made numerous efforts at revitalization.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In a proposal in 1995, Las Vegas developer Steve Wynn was to build a large casino, but that project failed due to traffic concerns.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The project was opposed as rival Donald Trump feared a Bridgeport casino would harm his Atlantic City properties and proposed to build a theme park and potential casino on the same site.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] New waves of migrants from places such as Brazil, Jamaica, Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia, Mexico, and other nations arrived in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Immigrants from Brazil, after the nation's inflation crisis, established themselves in the city due to the large Portuguese population already present, easing the language barrier.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was a common second US destination for Vietnamese refugees "There's already an established community here, so that's why they come," from the New York Times in 1996.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Along with them, Thai, Koreans, Chinese, and especially Laotians and Cambodians established themselves in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Likewise, the population from other Central and South American nations continued to increase while the Cuban population continued to decrease.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] "There has been a big shift in ethnic groups.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Just look at the restaurants that have opened in the last few years—Mexican, Brazilian, Chilean and Jamaican." an interviewee, local chamber of council president Paul Timpanelli stated in 2000 according to the Connecticut Post.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1999, city-owned Sikorsky Memorial Airport ceased its commercial regional flight offerings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2003, Mayor Ganim was involved in a corruption scandal after being investigated by the FBI as he received gifts from developers in exchange for being allowed to build in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] He was sentenced to federal prison, and was replaced by John Fabrizi.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the early 21st century, Bridgeport has taken steps toward redevelopment of its downtown and other neighborhoods.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2004, artists' lofts were developed in the former Read's Department Store on Broad Street.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Several other rental conversions have been completed, including the 117-unit Citytrust bank building on Main Street.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Great Recession halted, at least temporarily, two major mixed-use projects including a $1-billion waterfront development at Steel Point, but other redevelopment projects have proceeded, such as the condominium conversion project in Bijou Square.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2009, the City Council under Mayor Finch approved a new master plan for development, designed both to promote redevelopment in selected areas and to protect existing residential neighborhoods.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2010, the Bridgeport Housing Authority and a local health center announced plans to build a $20 million medical and housing complex at Albion Street, making use of federal stimulus funds and designed to replace some of the housing lost with the demolition of Father Panik Village.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Steel Point (or Steelpointe) project of Bridgeport's on the lower portion of the East Side finally led to the construction of a big box retailer in 2013, along with other stores, shops, and a lighthouse with a marina and oyster bar).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The plan for high-end mixed use apartments is in place, although concerns about gentrification have been raised.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A new proposed train station in East Bridgeport, meant to be completed in 2021, was postponed in 2019.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By 2013 the city and local business owners agreed that work needed to be done in the downtown area north of Fairfield Avenue, nicknamed Downtown North, above.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Made up of old empty brick buildings which were neglected for years, the city and developers began their rehabilitation starting in 2015, most of which are now converted apartments or retail.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport's downtown renovation has resulted in various restaurants, the renovation of the Bishop Arcade Mall, a comedy club, and theatres.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A 2022 plan to renovate McLevy Hall is in place.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2017, MGM had announced plans to build a waterfront casino and shopping center in the city, awaiting approval by the state government.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] If built, the development would have created 2,000 permanent jobs and about 5,779 temporary jobs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] After a legal battle with the Mohegan and Pequot tribes on the right to build a casino in Connecticut, the project "appears to be dead", and tenants such as Bridgeport Boatworks now occupy the proposed space.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The construction of Honey Locust Square began on the East End, which when complete will house a supermarket (something the neighborhood lacks), a public library, a health center, and a retail building.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] On March 10, 1860, Abraham Lincoln spoke in the city's Washington Hall, an auditorium at the old Bridgeport City Hall (now McLevy Hall), at the corner of State and Broad Streets.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest room in the city was packed, and a crowd formed outside, as well.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Lincoln received a standing ovation before taking the 9:07 pm train that night back to Manhattan.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A plaque marks the site where Lincoln spoke; later that year, he was elected president.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Martin Luther King Jr. spoke three times at the Klein Auditorium during the 1960s, as well as at the University of Bridgeport and the original Central High School (today Bridgeport City Hall)., as well as in Bridgeport City Hall.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bush spoke before a small group of Connecticut business people and officials at the Playhouse on the Green in 2006.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] President Barack Obama also spoke at the Harbor Yard arena in 2010 to gain support for the campaign of Democratic Governor Dan Malloy.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport lies along Long Island Sound at the mouth of the Pequonnock River.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has many distinct neighborhoods, divided into five geographic areas: Downtown, the East Side, the North End, the South End, and the West Side.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, Bridgeport straddles the humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) and humid continental climate (*Dfa*) zones with long, hot summers, and cool to cold winters, with precipitation spread fairly evenly throughout the year.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport, like the rest of coastal Connecticut, lies in the broad transition zone between the colder continental climates of the northern United States and southern Canada to the north, and the warmer temperate and subtropical climates of the middle and south Atlantic states to the south.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The warm/hot season in Bridgeport is from mid-April through early November.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Late day thundershowers are common in the hottest months (June, July, August, September), despite the mostly sunny skies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The cool/cold season is from late November though mid-March.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Winter weather is far more variable than summer weather along the Connecticut coast, ranging from sunny days with higher temperatures to cold and blustery conditions with occasional snow.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like much of the Connecticut coast and nearby Long Island, NY, most of the winter precipitation is rain or a mix and rain and wet snow in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport averages about 29 inches (75 cm) of snow annually, compared to inland areas like Hartford and Albany which average 45–60 inches (110–150 cm) of snow annually.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Although infrequent, tropical cyclones (hurricanes/tropical storms) have struck Connecticut and the Bridgeport metropolitan area.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hurricane landfalls have occurred along the Connecticut coast in 1903, 1938, 1944, 1954 (Carol), 1960 (Donna), Hurricane Gloria in 1985, and Hurricane Sandy in 2012.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport lies in USDA garden hardiness zone 7a, averaging about 92 days annually with freeze.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The coastal location of Bridgeport allows it to be milder than locations well south but inland.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For example, the record coldest low temperature at Atlanta is −8 °F, while the record coldest at Bridgeport is −7 °F.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Coastal Connecticut is the broad transition zone where so-called "subtropical indicator" plants such as cold hardy palms and other broadleaf evergreens can successfully be cultivated.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As such, southern magnolias, needle palms, windmill palm, loblolly pines, and crape myrtles are grown in private and public gardens.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like much of coastal Connecticut, Long Island, New York, and coastal New Jersey, the growing season is rather long in Bridgeport—averaging 210 days from April 8 to November 5 according to the National Weather Service in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The average monthly temperature ranges from 31.4 °F (−0.3 °C) in January to 75.7 °F (24.3 °C) in July.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Precipitation averages 44.9 inches (1,140 mm) annually, and is somewhat evenly distributed throughout the year, with March and April the wettest months.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As is typical of coastal Connecticut, snow cover does not usually last long, with an average of 33 days per winter with snow cover of at least 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As of the 2010 census, there were 144,229 people living in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 39.6% White; 34.6% Black or African American; 3.4% Asian; and 4.3% from two or more races.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A total of 38.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There were 50,307 households, out of which 34.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.0% were married couples living together, 24.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.9% were non-families.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 29.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The average household size was 2.70 and the average family size was 3.34.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the city, the population was spread out, with 28.4% under the age of 18, 11.2% from 18 to 24, 30.5% from 25 to 44, 18.4% from 45 to 64, and 11.5% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For every 100 females, there were 91.2 males.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.3 males.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $34,658, and the median income for a family was $39,571.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Males had a median income of $32,430 versus $26,966 for females.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The per capita income for the city was $16,306.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] About 16.2% of families and 18.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 24.8% of those under age 18 and 13.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] According to the 2020 five-year community survey, 48.2% of Bridgeport's population speaks a different primary language at home other than English, 33.8% percent of the city's total population speaks Spanish at home, and 22.5% speak English less than very well.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has the largest percentage and population of Hispanic Americans in the state of Connecticut.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 45,270 people (31%) of Bridgeport's population is foreign born in 2010.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other than Puerto Ricans, 5.4% of Bridgeport's population was noted under Mexican in 2013, a number that has grown to 5.8% (8,479 people) in the 2020 five-year American Community Survey, meaning Bridgeport has the largest Mexican population in New England.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Dominicans are 5,248 (3.53%) of Bridgeport's population.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The total Latino Central American population (Guatemalans, Salvadorians, Nicaraguans, Hondurans, Costa Ricans, Panamanians) is 6,701 people total in the city (4.507%).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 8,454 South Americans (5.697%); 4,020 Equadorians, 2,326 Colombians, Peruvians, and then populations from every Latin American nation except Bolivia can be found, with the smallest group being Paraguayans at 16 people according to the census.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport also has the largest Cuban population in the state, with more than 1,000 of the state's 10,600 Cubans living in Bridgeport, although down from the at least 5,000 Cubans in Bridgeport in 1980, and even more before that time in the 1950s according to the CTPost.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was once a major destination for migrating Cubans, but many families have since moved to the city's suburbs or Florida.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport, along with Danbury, CT were considered as a potential locations for a new Ecuadorian consulate, but it instead opened in New Haven, CT, due to its immigrant welcoming mayor, in 2008.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As for Portuguese-speaking peoples, the city also has the 12th largest Cape Verdean population in the country.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The group settled in the Hollow to work in factories and established a social club in the 1940s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Cape Verdean Association of Bridgeport is located in the Hollow today.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Portuguese community in the city is the largest in the state and the population primarily hails from the Tras Os Montes region of Portugal according to a 2018 research study, and the Hollow is considered the "Portuguese section" of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The large Brazilian population in Bridgeport and Danbury led to the opening of a Brazilian consulate in the state capital of Hartford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Migration to Connecticut began in the 90s, social networks brought immigrants from Governador Valadares, Minas Gerais in Brazil to Bridgeport, CT and Framingham, MA.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Fairfield County has the 7th largest Brazilian population of the United States, and 1/3rd of them live within Bridgeport's city limits, most of whom reside in the city's North End and St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A small population of people from various majority-Muslim nations exists along with Kurds, at least 4,000 according to an estimate by a local mosque in 2008.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Public Schools now observes Eid al-Fitr, effective 2024, thanks to a campaign by city 8th graders from Park City Magnet School, which found 10% of the school body was Muslim in a school project.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bengali in 2022 was the fifth most common primary language for Bridgeport Public School students (behind English, Spanish, Portuguese, and Haitian Creole, and is followed by Arabic at sixth place).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There is also a sizeable Kurdish population in Bridgeport, primarily from Iraq.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In total (and counting East and Southeast Asians), Bridgeport had 7,725 Asian residents according to the 2021 5 year American Community Survey, up from 2020's count, 5,553 Asians.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest national origin groups and their estimated populations are Vietnamese (1,258 people), Indian (1,153 people), Chinese, excluding Taiwanese and Pakistanis (both 982 people), and Filipinos (729 people).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other groups with over 500 people include Laotians and Cambodians, Bangladeshi Americans in the city numbered 385 people in the survey.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Jamaicans, the state's largest foreign-born group, have a significant presence in Bridgeport, with 6.3% of Bridgeport's population being Jamaican in 2013.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport in 2013 was 10.2% non-Hispanic West Indian.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] At least 92 languages are spoken as primary languages by Bridgeport Public School students according to district data in 2022.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 3,145 students are missing data in primary language.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Bridgeport-Stamford metropolitan area (i.e.: Fairfield County) is home to the 7th largest percentage of Italian ancestry in the country (the population is 16.5% Italian).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Italian Americans until 1985 were the largest ethnic group in Bridgeport itself, and had been since the 1920s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] According to 2010 census data, the Bridgeport MSA, containing all of Fairfield County, is the most economically unequal region in America, with 57% of the wealth going to the top income quintile.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As of the census of 2000, there were 139,529 people, 50,307 households, and 32,749 families living in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The population density was 8,720.9 inhabitants per square mile (3,367.2/km2).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There were 54,367 housing units at an average density of 3,398.1 per square mile (1,312.0/km2).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 45.0% White, 30.8% African American, 0.5% Native American, 3.3% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 31.9% of the population.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Since the decline of its industrial sector beginning in the middle of the 20th century, Bridgeport has gradually adjusted to a service-based economy.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] As late as 1985, the city was still home to company plants such as General Electric, with 1,900 employees, and Remington Products, with 900, both of which are now closed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bryant Electric didn't close its plant until 1988.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The last major factory to close was the Sikorsky helicopter plant in 2015.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Various famous industrial companies, that were founded and based in Bridgeport, such as ACME Sheer, Fortune 1000 Hubbell Incorporated, etc. are now based in suburban Shelton, two towns away.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Subway, which started out in Bridgeport in 1965, is now based in Milford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Though a level of industrial activity continues, healthcare, finance, and education have become the centerpieces of Bridgeport's economy.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The two largest employers in the city are Bridgeport's primary hospitals, Bridgeport Hospital and St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Park City Hospital in the South End closed in 1993 and was reopened in 2010 as elderly and homeless housing units.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In April 2022, M&T Bank of Buffalo, New York, merged with Bridgeport-based People's United Financial.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The combined company is now the 11th largest bank in the United States, and gave M&T a foothold in the New England market, in total serving 12 states.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Although M&T laid off Bridgeport employees (which made national headlines), the company as part of this effort made Bridgeport Center the regional M&T headquarters of New England.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was the annual home to Gathering of the Vibes, a weekend-long arts, music and camping festival, until it ended in 2015.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Beginning in 2022, Bridgeport played host to the Sound on Sound Music Festival, at Seaside Park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Past performers included; John Mayer, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Dave Matthews Band, Hozier, and The Roots.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The festival was rebranded in 2024 to Soundside Music Festival.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The 2025 Soundside Music Festival was cancelled.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Symphony, established in 1945, performs at Bridgeport's 1,400-seat Klein Memorial Auditorium.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Gustav Meier directed the orchestra from 1972 to 2013.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport metropolitan area is home to the Maritime Aquarium in Norwalk, 30 minutes from downtown Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] One of the two aquariums in Connecticut, the aquarium focuses on Long Island Sound as well as creatures and conservation efforts from around the world.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was once home to a Little Asia along Wood Avenue in the West Side, established in 2012 by local business owners with a sign and a festival every year.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] By 2016 the name had fallen out of use, and the committee no longer exists.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The more or less 3 or 4 block area is still home to Asian restaurants, an insurance and tax agency with Vietnamese, Mandarin, Laotian, Cantonese as well as Spanish language services, and a Vietnamese grocery store.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] NerdWallet ranked Bridgeport the 100th most foodie city in the United States, 2nd in Connecticut behind New Haven (which was ranked #97).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Nerdwallet in 2022 ranked Bridgeport as the 17th most ethnically diverse city in the United States, making it the most diverse in New England, and the third most diverse in the New York Metropolitan Area in an annual ranking.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is #28 on Niche.com "2022 Most Diverse Cities in America" list.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's Madison Avenue, and Hollow Brazilian restaurants, located alongside various Portuguese ones, have been mentioned by publications such as the *New York Times*.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Examples include churascaria restaurants.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is "among the top cities in the state to immerse yourself in Brazilian traditions" according to CTBites.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Azteca was ranked among the best Mexican restaurants in Connecticut in 2020 according to *Connecticut Magazine*, along with Pho Hong Thom and Pho Saigon in Bridgeport's Little Asia on the West Side for best Vietnamese places in the state.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Total Mortgage Arena serves as the city's sports and hospitality center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Seating 10,000, the Arena serves as the home rink of the Bridgeport Islanders American Hockey League team, the farm team of the New York Islanders of the National Hockey League.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Starting in 2024, it also serves as the home of the New York Sirens of the Professional Women's Hockey League.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The arena served as the temporary home of the Westchester Knicks of the NBA G League (the farm team for the NBA New York Knicks) from 2021 to 2023 when the team's home stadium, Westchester County Center in White Plains, New York iwas being used as a vaccination clinic.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] For college teams, Total Mortgage serves as the home court of Fairfield University's basketball team.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Ballpark at Harbor Yard served as a minor-league baseball stadium from 1998 to 2017.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It was built in 1998 to serve as the homefield of the Bridgeport Bluefish.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] From 2001 to 2003 it was the homefield for the Bridgeport Barrage, a Major League Lacrosse team.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is downtown on a former brownfield site.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is visually prominent to commuters on I-95 or on passing trains.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] On August 8, 2017, Mayor Joe Ganim announced that the Bluefish would be ending their 20-year stint at the ballpark at the end of the 2017 season.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The ballpark was converted into an amphitheatre.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bluefish played their final home game at the park on September 17, 2017, losing by a score of 9–2 to the Somerset Patriots.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Kennedy Stadium serves as a community sports facility.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, it was the home of an Atlantic Coast Football League minor league football team, the Bridgeport Jets, a New York Jets farm team also known locally as the Hi-Ho Jets due to their sponsorship by the (Hi-Ho) D'Addario construction company.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Fairfield University is in the neighboring town of Fairfield, and many of the athletic teams play on campus.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Only the men's and women's basketball teams play in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Nutmeg Curling Club, one of two curling clubs in Connecticut, is in Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is the home club of the 2013 USA Mixed National Champions, led by club members Derek Surka and Charissa Lin.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The club is a member of the Grand National Curling Club Region.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport native Jim O'Rourke was the first baseball player to earn a hit in National League history in 1876.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The founder and original owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers, Charles Ebbets, married his second wife in Bridgeport in 1922, five years before his death.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In early 2024, MLS Next Pro awarded an expansion team to Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Connecticut United FC plan to play at a new stadium to be located on the waterfront at a former dog-racing track, as stadium plans were approved by the Bridgeport government in November 2023.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Amateur soccer team GZS Bridgeport play in the UPSL, playing home games at Kennedy Stadium.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city has 1,300 acres of public space, with a pocket park in nearly every neighborhood.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's public park system led to its official nickname, "the Park City".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city's first public park was the westerly portion of McLevy Green, first set aside as a public square in 1806; the Clinton Park Militia Grounds (1666) and Old Mill Green (1717) were set aside earlier as public commons by the towns of Fairfield and Stratford, respectively.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Washington Park in 1850 was located in the center of East Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] As the city rapidly grew in population, residents recognized the need for more public parks and by 1864, Barnum, Nathaniel Wheeler and Colonel William Noble donated approximately 44 acres (18 ha) to create Seaside Park, now increased by acquisition and landfill to 375 acres (152 ha).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 1878, over 100 acres (40 ha) of land bordering the Pequonnock River was added as Beardsley Park.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Frederick Law Olmsted, who designed New York City's Central Park, designed both Seaside and Beardsley Parks.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Over time, more parks were added including 35-acre (14 ha) Beechwood Park and Pleasure Beach, home to an amusement park for many years.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Went Field on the West End, between Wordin Avenue and Norman Street, used to be the winter headquarters of Barnum's circus.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city is governed by the mayor-council system.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Twenty members of the city council are elected from districts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The mayor is elected at-large by the entire city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is notable for having had a socialist mayor for 24 years, Jasper McLevy, who served from 1933 to 1957.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Ganim, is a convicted felon who was sentenced to nine years in prison after conviction in 2003 of 16 federal counts including racketeering, extortion, conspiracy, bribery, mail fraud, and filing false tax returns arising from Ganim's "role in a six-year scheme to shake down city contractors…".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Fabrizi admitted that he had used cocaine while in office.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is recognized for its polarizing political culture.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Mayor Ganim has served the city seven terms since first taking office in 1991.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] After his release from prison in 2015, Ganim announced his mayoral campaign to serve a sixth term in office.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] His campaign ran on a theme of providing him with a "second-chance," as he was renowned for his work of escaping the city from bankruptcy and build its economy from a post-industrial standpoint.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's Democratic Town Committee has the authority to nominate and endorse Democratic candidates running for local office, and they have the resources to outperform challenger slates that may compete with them.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The chairman is former state representative and local restaurateur, Mario Testa.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport votes Democratic at the presidential level.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 1972 Richard Nixon was the last Republican to win the city; since then Democrats have prevailed, often by comfortable margins, the lone exception being 1984 when Walter Mondale carried the city by just 76 votes (0.16 percent) over Ronald Reagan.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport has one of the highest property tax rates in Connecticut.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 2016, Bridgeport enacted a 29% increase in the property tax rate, among the highest one-year property tax rate increases in recent U.S. history, in an effort to reduce the municipal deficit.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] A citywide reassessment in 2015 determined that the value of taxable property in the city was $6 billion, a decline of $1 billion; the property tax increases, combined with property value decreases, have been a consistent political issue in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is home to the University of Bridgeport, Housatonic Community College, Saint Vincent's College, and the Yeshiva Gedola of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Yeshiva Gedola is the home of the Bridgeport Community Kollel, a rabbinic fellowship program.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The University of Bridgeport's Ernest C.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Trefz School of Business offers undergraduate and graduate programs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sacred Heart University is located in the neighboring suburb of Fairfield on the town line, with its campus extending into the North End of Bridgeport on Park Avenue.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Many of its students live in the city's North End.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is the second largest Catholic University in New England (behind Boston College).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sacred Heart has campuses in nearby Stamford, as well as Griswold, CT and Dingle, Ireland, as well as St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The University of Bridgeport has secondary campuses in Waterbury and Stamford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Area (made up of the surrounding towns) is home to Fairfield University in neighboring Fairfield, and Western Connecticut State University in Danbury.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city's public school system has 30 elementary schools, three comprehensive high schools, two alternative programs and an interdistrict vocational aquaculture school.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The system has about 20,800 students, making the Bridgeport Public Schools the second largest school system in Connecticut after Hartford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is ranked #158 out of the 164 Connecticut school districts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The school system employs a professional staff of more than 1,700.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city has started a large school renovation and construction program, with plans for new schools and modernization of existing buildings.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is also home to private schools including Bridgeport Hope School (K–8), Bridgeport International Academy (grades 9–12), Catholic Academies of Bridgeport (Pre-K–8), Kolbe Cathedral High School (9–12), St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was NBC's pioneer UHF TV test site from December 29, 1949, to August 23, 1952; the equipment from the "Operation Bridgeport" tests was later deployed commercially at KPTV in Portland, Oregon (1952–1957).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sikorsky Memorial Airport in neighboring Stratford is owned by the City of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It once provided regional flights to major cities, but commercial operations at the airport were terminated in November 1999.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Interstate 95 and the Route 8/Route 25 Connector meet in Downtown Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] I-95 runs east–west near the coast heading towards New York City to the southwest and Providence to the northeast.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Routes 8 and 25 run north–south across the city, with the two routes splitting just north of the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Route 8 continues towards Waterbury and Torrington and Route 25 continues towards the Danbury area.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Both Routes 8 and 25 connect to the Merritt Parkway in the adjacent town of Trumbull.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] 1 (the Boston Post Road), which runs east–west north of Downtown, and Main Street, which runs north–south towards Trumbull center.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city also has several secondary state highways, namely, Route 127 (East Main Street), Route 130 (Connecticut Avenue, Stratford Avenue, Fairfield Avenue and Water Street), and the Huntington Turnpike.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Traction Company provided streetcar service in the region until 1937.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Housatonic Railroad carried passengers North through the Pequonnock and Housatonic Valleys before 1933.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city is connected to nearby New York City by both Amtrak and Metro-North commuter trains, which serve Bridgeport's Metro-North station.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Many residents commute to New York jobs on these trains, and the city to some extent is developing as an outpost of New York–based workers seeking cheaper rents and larger living spaces.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Connecting service is also available to Waterbury via Metro-North, and New Haven via Amtrak and Metro-North.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Shoreline East service links Old Saybrook and New London with New Haven, which extends to Bridgeport and Stamford during weekday rush hours only.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport & Port Jefferson Ferry service runs from Bridgeport across Long Island Sound to Port Jefferson, New York; the four vessels *Grand Republic*, *P.T.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Barnum*, Long Island and *Park City* transport both automobiles and passengers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Transit Authority (GBTA) provides bus service to Bridgeport and its immediate suburbs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Route 2 the Coastal Link goes west to Norwalk and east to the Connecticut Post Mall in Milford, from where Connecticut Transit can bring passengers to the New Haven Green.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Greyhound and Peter Pan Bus Lines both offer intercity bus service to points throughout the Northeast and points beyond.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Fire Department provides fire protection and emergency medical services at the Basic life support level to the city of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Police Department is the primary law enforcement agency in Bridgeport, Fairfield County, Connecticut, United States.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is responsible for most law enforcement within the geographical boundaries of City of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Connecticut State Police Troop G barracks is located in Bridgeport but they do not primarily perform law enforcement functions in the city.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Emergency medical services are provided by American Medical Response at the paramedic level.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The **Douglas Aircraft Company** was an American aerospace and defense company that was based in Southern California.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] It was founded in 1921 by Donald Wills Douglas Sr., and merged with McDonnell Aircraft in 1967 to form McDonnell Douglas, where it operated as a division.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company was founded as the Douglas Company by Donald Wills Douglas Sr. on July 22, 1921, in Santa Monica, California, following dissolution of the Davis-Douglas Company.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] An early claim to fame was the first circumnavigation of the world by air in Douglas airplanes in 1924.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Army Air Service was interested in carrying out a mission to circumnavigate the Earth for the first time by aircraft, a program called "World Flight".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Donald Douglas proposed a modified Douglas DT to meet the Army's needs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The two-place, open cockpit DT biplane torpedo bomber had previously been produced for the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The DTs were taken from the assembly lines at the company's manufacturing plants in Rock Island, Illinois, and Dayton, Ohio, to be modified.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The modified aircraft known as the Douglas World Cruiser (DWC), also was the first major project for Jack Northrop who designed the fuel system for the series.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] After the prototype was delivered in November 1923, upon the successful completion of tests on November 19, the Army commissioned Douglas to build four production series aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Due to the demanding expedition ahead, spare parts, including 15 extra Liberty L-12 engines, 14 extra sets of pontoons, and enough replacement airframe parts for two more aircraft were chosen.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] These were sent to airports along the route.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The last of these aircraft was delivered to the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] After the success of this flight, the Army Air Service ordered six similar aircraft as observation aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The success of the DWC established the Douglas Aircraft Company among the major aircraft companies of the world and led it to adopt the motto "First Around the World – First the World Around".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas initially used a logo that combined two letter Ds with two outstretched wings, and two Ds placed back to back to form a heart as a reference to Clan Douglas.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] After the success of the DWC, the company adopted a logo that showed three airplanes circling a globe.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The logo eventually evolved into an aircraft, a missile, and a globe.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] This logo was later adopted by McDonnell Douglas in 1967, and became the basis of Boeing's current logo after their merger in 1997.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas Aircraft designed and built a wide variety of aircraft for the U.S. military, including the Navy, Army Air Forces, Marine Corps, Air Force, and Coast Guard.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company initially built torpedo bombers for the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Navy, but it developed a number of different versions of these aircraft, including reconnaissance planes and airmail aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Within five years, the company was building about 100 aircraft annually.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Among the early employees at Douglas were Ed Heinemann, "Dutch" Kindelberger, Carl Cover, and Jack Northrop, who later founded the Northrop Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] In the mid-1920s the company had manufacturing facilities in Santa Monica at what is now Douglas Park at 25th Street and Wilshire Boulevard.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company retained its military market and expanded into amphibian airplanes in the late 1920s, also moving its facilities to Clover Field at Santa Monica, California.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The Santa Monica complex was so large, the mail girls used roller skates to deliver the intracompany mail.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] By the end of World War II, Douglas had facilities at Santa Monica, El Segundo, Long Beach, and Torrance, California; Tulsa and Midwest City, Oklahoma; and Chicago, Illinois.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] On November 30, 1928, the company was reorganized as the Douglas Aircraft Company.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] In 1934, Douglas produced a commercial twin-engined transport plane, the Douglas DC-2, followed by the famous DC-3 in 1936.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The wide range of aircraft produced by Douglas included airliners, light and medium bombers, fighter aircraft, transports, reconnaissance aircraft, and experimental aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Many Douglas aircraft have long service lives.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] During World War II, Douglas joined the BVD (Boeing-Vega-Douglas) consortium to produce the B-17 Flying Fortress.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] After the war, Douglas built another Boeing design under license, the B-47 Stratojet turbojet-powered bomber, using a government-owned factory in Marietta, Georgia.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] World War II was a major boost for Douglas.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas ranked fifth among United States corporations in the value of wartime production contracts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company produced almost 30,000 aircraft from 1942 to 1945, and its workforce swelled to 160,000.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company produced a number of aircraft including the C-47 Skytrain, the DB-7 (known as the A-20, Havoc or Boston), the SBD Dauntless dive bomber, and the A-26 Invader.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas Aircraft suffered cutbacks at the end of the war, with an end to government aircraft orders and a surplus of aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] It was necessary to cut heavily into its workforce, letting go of nearly 100,000 workers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The United States Army Air Forces established 'Project RAND' (Research ANd Development) with the objective of looking into long-range planning of future weapons.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] In March 1946, Douglas Aircraft Company was granted the contract to research on intercontinental warfare.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Project RAND later become the RAND Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas continued to develop new aircraft, including the successful four-engined Douglas DC-6 (1946) and its last propeller-driven commercial aircraft, the Douglas DC-7 (1953).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company had moved into jet propulsion, producing its first for the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Navy — the straight-winged F3D Skyknight in 1948 and then the more "jet age" style F4D Skyray in 1951.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas also made commercial jets, producing the Douglas DC-8 in 1958 to compete with the new Boeing 707.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas was a pioneer in related fields, such as ejection seats, air-to-air missiles, surface-to-air missiles, and air-to-surface missiles, launch rockets, bombs, and bomb racks.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company was ready to enter the new missile business during the 1950s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas moved from producing air-to-air rockets and missiles to entire missile systems under the 1956 Nike missile program and became the main contractor for the Skybolt air-launched ballistic missile program and the Thor ballistic missile program.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas also earned contracts from NASA, most notably for designing the S-IVB stage of the Saturn IB and Saturn V rockets.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] In 1967, the company was struggling to expand production to meet demand for DC-8 and DC-9 airliners and the A-4 Skyhawk military attack aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The company was also struggling with quality and cash flow problems and DC-10 development costs, as well as shortages due to the Vietnam War.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Under the circumstances, Douglas was very receptive to an offer from McDonnell Aircraft Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] On April 28, 1967, after almost four years of merger talks, the two companies merged as McDonnell Douglas Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The two companies seemed to be a good match for each other.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] McDonnell was a major defense contractor, but had almost no civilian business.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas' commercial contracts would allow McDonnell to withstand any downturns in procurement.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Conversely, McDonnell had enough revenue to help solve Douglas' financial problems; soon after the merger was announced, McDonnell bought 1.5 million shares of Douglas stock to help Douglas meet "immediate financial requirements".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The merged company was based at McDonnell's facility in St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] It adopted a modified version of Douglas' logo.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Donald Wills Douglas Sr. became honorary chairman of the merged company, a post he would hold until his death in 1981.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Douglas Aircraft Company continued as a wholly owned subsidiary of McDonnell Douglas, with Douglas' son, Donald Wills Douglas Jr., as president.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Later, former McDonnell president David S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Lewis became chairman of Douglas Aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] His successful turnaround of the division allowed him to become president of McDonnell Douglas in 1969.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Meanwhile, Douglas' space and missiles division became part of a new subsidiary called McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Company.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] McDonnell Douglas later merged with its rival Boeing in 1997.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] Boeing merged Douglas Aircraft into the Boeing Commercial Airplanes division, and retired the Douglas Aircraft name after 76 years.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] The last Long Beach-built commercial aircraft, the Boeing 717 (third generation version of the Douglas DC-9), ceased production in May 2006.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] By 2011, the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III was the last aircraft being assembled at the Long Beach facility; the final C-17 was assembled in late 2015.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/douglas-aircraft-company] However, the Douglas' former logo is preserved on the facility though no longer used by Boeing.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] An **engineer** is a practitioner of engineering.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The word *engineer* (Latin *ingeniator*, Ir is the term and or title of an engineer in countries like Belgium, The Netherlands, and Indonesia) is derived from the Latin words *ingeniare* ("to contrive, devise") and *ingenium* ("cleverness").
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The work of engineers forms the link between scientific discoveries and their subsequent applications to human and business needs and quality of life.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers develop new technological solutions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] During the engineering design process, the responsibilities of the engineer may include defining problems, conducting and narrowing research, analyzing criteria, finding and analyzing solutions, and making decisions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Much of an engineer's time is spent on researching, locating, applying, and transferring information.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Indeed, research suggests engineers spend 56% of their time engaged in various information behaviours, including 14% actively searching for information.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers weigh different design choices on their merits and choose the solution that best matches the requirements and needs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Their task is to identify, understand, and interpret the constraints on a design in order to produce a successful result.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The work of an engineer requires problem solving skills.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers apply techniques of engineering analysis in testing, production, or maintenance.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Analytical engineers may supervise production in factories and elsewhere, determine the causes of a process failure, and test output to maintain quality.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] They also estimate the time and cost required to complete projects.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Supervisory engineers are responsible for major components or entire projects.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineering analysis involves the application of scientific analytic principles and processes to reveal the properties and state of the system, device or mechanism under study.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineering analysis proceeds by separating the engineering design into the mechanisms of operation or failure, analyzing or estimating each component of the operation or failure mechanism in isolation, and recombining the components.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Many engineers use computers to produce and analyze designs, to simulate and test how a machine, structure, or system operates, to generate specifications for parts, to monitor the quality of products, and to control the efficiency of processes.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Most engineers specialize in one or more engineering disciplines.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Numerous specialties are recognized by professional societies, and each of the major branches of engineering has numerous subdivisions.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Civil engineering, for example, includes structural engineering, along with transportation engineering, geotechnical engineering, and materials engineering, including ceramic, metallurgical, and polymer engineering.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Mechanical engineering cuts across most disciplines since its core essence is applied physics.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers also may specialize in one industry, such as motor vehicles, or in one type of technology, such as turbines or semiconductor materials.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Several recent studies have investigated how engineers spend their time; that is, the work tasks they perform and how their time is distributed among these.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Research suggests that there are several key themes present in engineers' work: technical work (i.e., the application of science to product development), social work (i.e., interactive communication between people), computer-based work and information behaviors.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Among other more detailed findings, a 2012 work sampling study found that engineers spend 62.92% of their time engaged in technical work, 40.37% in social work, and 49.66% in computer-based work.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Furthermore, there was considerable overlap between these different types of work, with engineers spending 24.96% of their time engaged in technical and social work, 37.97% in technical and non-social, 15.42% in non-technical and social, and 21.66% in non-technical and non-social.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The time engineers spend engaged in such activities is also reflected in the competencies required in engineering roles.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In addition to engineers' core technical competence, research has also demonstrated the critical nature of their personal attributes, project management skills, and cognitive abilities to success in the role.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] There are many branches of engineering, each of which specializes in specific technologies and products.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Typically, engineers will have deep knowledge in one area and basic knowledge in related areas.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] For example, mechanical engineering curricula typically include introductory courses in electrical engineering, computer science, materials science, metallurgy, mathematics, and software engineering.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] An engineer may either be hired for a firm that requires engineers on a continuous basis, or may belong to an engineering firm that provides engineering consulting services to other firms.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] When developing a product, engineers typically work in interdisciplinary teams.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] For example, when building robots an engineering team will typically have at least three types of engineers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] A mechanical engineer would design the body and actuators.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] An electrical engineer would design the power systems, sensors, electronics, embedded software in electronics, and control circuitry.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Finally, a software engineer would develop the software that makes the robot behave properly.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers that aspire to management engage in further study in business administration, project management and organizational or business psychology.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Often engineers move up the management hierarchy from managing projects, functional departments, and divisions, and some eventually become CEOs of multi-national corporations.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineers have obligations to the public, their clients, employers, and the profession.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Many engineering societies have established codes of practice and codes of ethics to guide members and inform the public at large.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Each engineering discipline and professional society maintains a code of ethics, which the members pledge to uphold.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Depending on their specializations, engineers may also be governed by specific statute, whistleblowing, product liability laws, and often the principles of business ethics.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Some graduates of engineering programs in North America may be recognized by the iron ring or Engineer's Ring, a ring made of iron or stainless steel that is worn on the little finger of the dominant hand.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] This tradition began in 1925 in Canada with The Ritual of the Calling of an Engineer, where the ring serves as a symbol and reminder of the engineer's obligations to the engineering profession.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In 1972, the practice was adopted by several colleges in the United States including members of the Order of the Engineer.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Most engineering programs involve a concentration of study in an engineering specialty, along with courses in both mathematics and the physical and life sciences.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Many programs also include courses in general engineering and applied accounting.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] A design course, often accompanied by a computer or laboratory class or both, is part of the curriculum of most programs.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Often, general courses not directly related to engineering, such as those in the social sciences or humanities, also are required.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Accreditation is the process by which engineering programs are evaluated by an external body to determine if applicable standards are met.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The Washington Accord serves as an international accreditation agreement for academic engineering degrees, recognizing the substantial equivalency in the standards set by many major national engineering bodies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the United States, post-secondary degree programs in engineering are accredited by the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In many countries, engineering tasks such as the design of bridges, electric power plants, industrial equipment, machine design and chemical plants, must be approved by a licensed professional engineer.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Most commonly titled professional engineer is a license to practice and is indicated with the use of post-nominal letters; PE or P.Eng.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] These are common in North America, as is European engineer (EUR ING) in Europe.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the United States, engineering is a regulated profession whose practice and practitioners are licensed and governed by law.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Licensure is generally attainable through combination of education, pre-examination (Fundamentals of Engineering exam), examination (professional engineering exam), and engineering experience (typically in the area of 5+ years).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Each state tests and licenses professional engineers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Currently, most states do not license by specific engineering discipline, but rather provide generalized licensure, and trust engineers to use professional judgment regarding their individual competencies; this is the favoured approach of the professional societies.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Despite this, at least one of the examinations required by most states is actually focused on a particular discipline; candidates for licensure typically choose the category of examination which comes closest to their respective expertise.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Such person does not have the final authority to approve, or the ultimate responsibility for, engineering designs, plans, or specifications that are to be incorporated into fixed works, systems, or facilities on the property of others or made available to the public.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In some instances, some positions, such as a "sanitation engineer", does not have any basis in engineering sciences.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Each state has different requirements on years of experience to take the Fundamentals of Engineering (FE) and Professional Engineering (PE) exams.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] A few states require a graduate MS in engineering to sit for the exams as further learning.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] After seven years of working after graduation, two years of responsibility for significant engineering work, continuous professional development, some highly qualified PEs are able to become International Professional Engineers Int(PE).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] These engineers must meet the highest level of professional competencies and this is a peer-reviewed process.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Once the IntPE title is awarded, the engineer can gain easier admission to national registers of a number of members jurisdictions for international practice.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Canada, engineering is a self-regulated profession.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The profession in each province is governed by its own engineering association.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Continental Europe, Latin America, Turkey, and elsewhere the title is limited by law to people with an engineering degree and the use of the title by others is illegal.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Italy, the title is limited to people who hold an engineering degree, have passed a professional qualification examination (*Esame di Stato*) and are enrolled in the register of the local branch of National Associations of Engineers (a public body).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Portugal, professional engineer titles and accredited engineering degrees are regulated and certified by the *Ordem dos Engenheiros*.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the Czech Republic, the title "engineer" (Ing.) is given to people with a (master's) degree in chemistry, technology or economics for historical and traditional reasons.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Greece, the academic title of "Diploma Engineer" is awarded after completion of the five-year engineering study course and the title of "Certified Engineer" is awarded after completion of the four-year course of engineering studies at a Technological Educational Institute (TEI).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The definition of the term "engineer" varies across countries and continents.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the Indian subcontinent, Russia, Middle East, Africa, and China, engineering is one of the most sought-after undergraduate courses, for which entrance examinations are highly competitive.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the Philippines and Filipino communities overseas, engineers who are either Filipino or not, especially those who also profess other jobs at the same time, are addressed and introduced as *Engineer*, rather than *Sir/Madam* in speech or *Mr./Mrs./Ms.* (*G./Gng./Bb.* in Filipino) before surnames.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] That word is used either in itself or before the given name or surname.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] As of 2022, thirty two countries in Europe (including nearly all 27 countries of the EU) now recognise the title of "European Engineer" which permits the use of the pre-nominal title of "EUR ING" (always fully capitalised).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Each country sets its own precise qualification requirement for the use of the title (though they are all broadly equivalent).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Holding the requisite qualification does not afford automatic entitlement.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The title has to be applied for (and the appropriate fee paid).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The holder is entitled to use the title in their passport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] EUR INGs are allowed to describe themselves as professionally qualified engineers and practise as such in any of the 32 participating countries including those where the title of engineer is regulated by law.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In France, the term *ingénieur* (engineer) is not a protected title and can be used by anyone who practices this profession.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] However, the title *ingénieur diplomé* (graduate engineer) is an official academic title that is protected by the government and is associated with the *Diplôme d'Ingénieur*, which is a renowned academic degree in France.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Anyone misusing this title in France can be fined a large sum and jailed, as it is usually reserved for graduates of French engineering *grandes écoles*.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineering schools which were created during the French revolution have a special reputation among the French people, as they helped to make the transition from a mostly agricultural country of late 18th century to the industrially developed France of the 19th century.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] A great part of 19th-century France's economic wealth and industrial prowess was created by engineers that have graduated from École Centrale Paris, École des Mines de Paris, École polytechnique or Télécom Paris.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] This was also the case after WWII when France had to be rebuilt.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Before the "réforme René Haby" in the 1970s, it was very difficult to be admitted to such schools, and the French *ingénieurs* were commonly perceived as the nation's élite.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] However, after the Haby reform and a series of further reforms (Modernization plans of French universities), several engineering schools were created which can be accessed with relatively lower competition.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Engineering positions in France are now shared between the *ingénieurs diplomés* graduating from engineering *grandes écoles* and the holders of a master's degree in science from public universities.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Italy, only people who hold a formal engineering qualification of at least a bachelor's degree are permitted to describe themselves as an engineer.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In the UK, the practice of engineering is not a regulated profession but control of the titles of chartered engineer (CEng) and incorporated engineer (IEng) is regulated.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] These titles are protected by law and are subject to strict requirements defined by the Engineering Council.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The title CEng is in use in nations of the Commonwealth of Nations that follow or adapt British professional codes.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Many skilled and semi-skilled tradespeople in the UK, including, for example, engineering technicians who service domestic appliances or telephone systems, call themselves engineers, and the term in that context is commonly used by the public.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In Canada, engineering is a regulated profession whose practice and practitioners are licensed and governed by law.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Licensed professional engineers are referred to as P.Eng.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Many Canadian engineers wear an Iron Ring.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] In all Canadian provinces, the title "Professional Engineer" is protected by law and any non-licensed individual or company using the title is committing a legal offence and is subject to fines and restraining orders.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Contrary to insistence from the Professional Engineers Ontario ("PEO") and Engineers Canada, use of the title "Engineer" itself has been found by Canadian law to be acceptable by those not holding P.Eng. titles.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The title of engineer is not exclusive to P.Eng titles.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The title of Engineer is commonly held by "Software Engineer", the Canadian Military as various ranks and positions, railway locomotive engineers, Stationary engineer and Aircraft Maintenance Engineers (AME), all of which do not commonly hold a P.Eng. designation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Certain Spanish-speaking countries follow the Italian convention of engineers using the pre-nominal title, in this case "*ingeniero*" (or "*ingeniera*" if female).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] Like in Italy, it is usually abbreviated to "Ing." In Spain this practice is not followed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/engineer] The engineering profession enjoys high prestige in Spain, ranking close to medical doctors, scientists and professors, and above judges, journalists or entrepreneurs, according to a 2014 study.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Petersburg, Russia in 1916, was the oldest of two children, born to Michael E.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff was an aircraft engineer who was a former Chief engineer at the Sikorsky Aircraft division of the United Aircraft Corporation, who graduated from the Russian Imperial Military Engineering College (now known as the Saint Petersburg Military Engineering-Technical University).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff graduated from the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in 1944 with a Bachelor of Sciences in Aeronautical Engineering.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Immediately after his graduation, Gluhareff went to work at Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in Bridgeport, Connecticut; where he worked under Igor A.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff began his career at the Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in 1944, one of the initial projects he worked on included the VS-300 and the R-4 helicopters.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff began working on the Pulse Jet Engine in 1947 for Sikorsky.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1950, Gluhareff moved to California in order to work with the company, American Helicopter.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] One of the helicopters he worked on during the early 1950s was the XA-5 "Top Sergeant", a valved pulse-jet powered helicopter.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1953, after working on several other projects, Gluhareff founded the Gluhareff Helicopters Corporation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Navy in order to develop Rotary Drones in 1960.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1964, Gluhareff joined the Douglas Aircraft Company, where he worked as a Design Engineer Scientist in the development of the S-4 stage of the Saturn Rocket which was part of the Apollo program.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff continued to work with the company, as it became the McDonnell Douglas company, where he eventually became a specialist in rocket stabilization system designing used for ejection seats and capsules.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff returned to EMG Engineering, his own company in 1972, where he continued working until his death, one of the last projects he worked on was the EMG-300, also known as the "Flying Motorcycle", which was designed in the early 1990s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff died due to illness whilst he was working on the production and marketing stage of the EMG-300 helicopter in 1994.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-emg-300] The **Gluhareff EMG-300** is a single-seat helicopter with a rotor powered by tip jet engines.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-emg-300] It was designed and built by Eugene Michael Gluhareff in the 1990s.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-emg-300] Although some test flights took place, Gluhareff died in 1994 before development was completed.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-emg-300] The helicopter has a two-blade rotor; each blade has a Gluhareff Pressure Jet engine mounted on its tip.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-emg-300] Only one was built; it is now in the collection of the Pima Air & Space Museum in Tucson, Arizona.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The **Gluhareff Pressure Jet** (or **tip jet**) is a type of jet engine that, like a valveless pulse jet, has no moving parts.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] It was invented by Eugene Michael Gluhareff, a Russian-American engineer who envisioned it as a power plant for personal helicopters and compact aircraft such as microlights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Having no moving parts, the engine works by having a coiled pipe in the combustion chamber that superheats the fuel (propane) before being injected into the air-fuel inlet.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] In the combustion chamber, the fuel/air mixture ignites and burns, creating thrust as it leaves through the exhaust pipe.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Induction and compression of the fuel/air mixture is done both by the pressure of propane as it is injected, along with the sound waves created by combustion acting on the intake stacks.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The engine has three intake stages, which are sized according to the sound created by the combustion process when running.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] This has exactly the same effect as the turbine and compressor in a turbojet, creating a vacuum that sucks in air.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The intakes, along with the exhaust, are sonically tuned so that the locations of the pressure antinodes of the Mach disks in the propane stream match the locations of the intake apertures.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Thus atmospheric pressure augments air intake as much as possible.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Early prototypes produced very small amounts of thrust, before Gluharev developed it from early experiments on producing thrust from using the pressurized fuel's kinetic energy to suck in the air and compress it prior to combustion.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] A 1949 reference to a very similar concept exists.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Although described as a ram jet, this version heats the fuel within a closed space to create the pressure for injection and compression of the entrained air in a similar manner to the Gluhareff design and is in all fundamental respects a pressure jet of the same type.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] After emigrating to the United States in 1919 because of the Russian Revolution, Sikorsky founded the Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in 1923 and developed the first of Pan American Airways' ocean-crossing flying boats in the 1930s, including the Sikorsky S-42 "Flying Clipper".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1939, Sikorsky designed and flew the Vought-Sikorsky VS-300, the first viable American helicopter, which pioneered the single main rotor and a single antitorque tail rotor configuration used by most helicopters today.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky modified the design into the Sikorsky R-4, which became the world's first mass-produced helicopter in 1942.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Igor Sikorsky was born in Kiev, Russian Empire (now Kyiv, Ukraine), on May 25, 1889.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] His father, Ivan Alexeevich Sikorsky, was a professor of psychology in Saint Vladimir University (now Taras Shevchenko National University), a psychiatrist with an international reputation, and an ardent Russian nationalist.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Igor Sikorsky was an Orthodox Christian.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] When questioned regarding his roots, he would answer: "My family is of Russian origin.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky's mother, Mariya Stefanovna Sikorskaya (née Temryuk-Cherkasova), was a physician who did not work professionally.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] She is sometimes called Zinaida Sikorsky.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] While homeschooling young Igor, she gave him a great love for art, especially in the life and work of Leonardo da Vinci, and the stories of Jules Verne.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1900, at age 11, he accompanied his father to Germany and through conversations with his father became interested in natural sciences.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] After returning home, Sikorsky began to experiment with model flying machines, and by age 12, he had made a small rubber band-powered helicopter.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky began studying at the Saint Petersburg Maritime Cadet Corps in 1903 at the age of 14.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1906, he determined that his future lay in engineering, so he resigned from the academy, despite his satisfactory standing, and left the Russian Empire to study in Paris.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He returned to the Russian Empire in 1907, enrolling at the Mechanical College of the Kiev Polytechnic Institute.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] After the academic year, Sikorsky again accompanied his father to Germany in the summer of 1908, where he learned of the accomplishments of the Wright brothers' *Flyer* and Ferdinand von Zeppelin's rigid airships.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky later said about this event: "Within twenty-four hours, I decided to change my life's work.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] By the start of World War I in 1914, Sikorsky's airplane research and production business in Kiev was flourishing, and his factory made bombers during the war.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] After the Russian Revolution in 1917, Igor Sikorsky fled his homeland in early 1918, because the Bolsheviks threatened to shoot him for being "the Tsar's friend and a very popular person".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He moved to France where he was offered a contract for the design of a new, more powerful Muromets-type plane.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] But in November 1918 the war ended, and the French government stopped subsidizing military orders, whereupon he decided to move to the United States.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] On March 24, 1919, he left France on the ocean liner *Lorraine*, arriving in New York City on March 30, 1919.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] With financial backing from his sister Olga, Sikorsky returned to Paris, the center of the aviation world at the time, in 1909.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky met with aviation pioneers, to ask them questions about aircraft and flying.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In May 1909, he returned to Russia and began designing his first helicopter, which he began testing in July 1909.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Powered by a 25-horsepower (19-kilowatt) Anzani engine, the helicopter used an upper and lower two-bladed lifting propeller that rotated in opposite directions at 160 rpm.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The machine could only generate about 357 pounds-force (1,590 newtons) of lift, not enough to lift the approximate 457 pounds (207 kg) weight.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Despite his progress in solving technical problems of control, Sikorsky realized that the aircraft would never fly.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He finally disassembled the aircraft in October 1909, after he determined that he could learn nothing more from the design.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In February 1910, he undertook to build a second helicopter, and his first airplane.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] 2 could lift its weight of 400 pounds (180 kg), but not the additional weight of an operator.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky's first aircraft of his own design, the S-1, used a 15 hp (11 kW) Anzani 3-cylinder fan engine in a pusher configuration, that could not lift the aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] His second design, called the S-2, was powered by a 25 hp (19 kW) Anzani engine in a tractor configuration and first flew on June 3, 1910, at a height of a few feet.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] On June 30, after some modifications, Sikorsky reached an altitude of "sixty or eighty feet" before the S-2 stalled and was completely destroyed when it crashed in a ravine.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Later, Sikorsky built the two-seat S-5, his first design not based on other European aircraft.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Flying this original aircraft, Sikorsky earned his pilot license; Fédération Aéronautique Internationale (FAI) license No.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] 64 issued by the Imperial Aero Club of Russia in 1911.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] During a demonstration of the S-5, the engine quit and Sikorsky was forced to make a crash landing to avoid a wall.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] It was discovered that a mosquito in the gasoline had been drawn into the carburetor, starving the engine of fuel.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The close call convinced Sikorsky of the need for an aircraft that could continue flying if it lost an engine.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] His next aircraft, the S-6 held three passengers and was selected as the winner of the Moscow aircraft exhibition held by the Russian Army in February 1912.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In early 1912, Igor Sikorsky became Chief Engineer of the aircraft division for the Russian Baltic Railroad Car Works (*Russko-Baltiisky Vagonny Zavod* or *R-BVZ*) in Saint Petersburg.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He also served as the test pilot for its first flight on May 13, 1913.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In recognition of his accomplishment, he was awarded an honorary degree in engineering from Saint Petersburg Polytechnical Institute in 1914.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky took the experience from building the Russky Vityaz to develop the S-22 *Ilya Muromets* airliner.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Due to the outbreak of World War I, he redesigned it as the world's first four-engined bomber, for which he was decorated with the Order of St.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] After World War I, Igor Sikorsky briefly became an engineer for the French forces in Russia, during the Russian Civil War.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Seeing little opportunity for himself as an aircraft designer in war-torn Europe, and particularly Russia, ravaged by the Bolshevik Revolution and Russian Civil War, he emigrated to the United States, arriving in New York on March 30, 1919.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In the U.S., Sikorsky first worked as a school teacher and a lecturer, while looking for an opportunity to work in the aviation industry.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1932, he joined the faculty of the University of Rhode Island to form an aeronautical engineering program and remained with the university until 1948.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He also lectured at the University of Bridgeport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1923, Sikorsky formed the Sikorsky Manufacturing Company in Roosevelt, New York.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] He was helped by several former Russian military officers.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Among Sikorsky's chief supporters was composer Sergei Rachmaninoff, who introduced himself by writing a check for US$5,000 (equivalent to $94,482 in 2025).
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Although his prototype was damaged in its first test flight, Sikorsky persuaded his reluctant backers to invest another $2,500.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] With the additional funds, he produced the S-29, one of the first twin-engine aircraft in the U.S., with a capacity for 14 passengers and a speed of 115 mph.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The performance of the S-29, slow when compared to military aircraft of 1918, proved to be a "make or break" moment for Sikorsky's funding.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1928, Sikorsky became a naturalized citizen of the United States.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The Sikorsky Manufacturing Company moved to Stratford, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] It became a part of the United Aircraft and Transport Corporation (now United Technologies Corporation) in July of that year.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The company manufactured flying boats, such as the S-42 "Clipper", used by Pan Am for transatlantic flights.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Meanwhile, Sikorsky also continued his earlier work on vertical flight while living in Nichols, Connecticut.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] On February 14, 1929, he filed an application to patent a "direct lift" amphibian aircraft which used compressed air to power a direct lift "propeller" and two smaller propellers for thrust.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] On June 27, 1931, Sikorsky filed for a patent for another "direct lift aircraft", and was awarded patent No.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] His design plans eventually culminated in the first (tethered) flight of the Vought-Sikorsky VS-300 on September 14, 1939, with the first free flight occurring eight months later on May 24, 1940.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky's success with the VS-300 led to the R-4, which became the world's first mass-produced helicopter, in 1942.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky's final VS-300 rotor configuration, comprising a single main rotor and a single antitorque tail rotor, has proven to be one of the most popular helicopter configurations, being used in most helicopters produced today.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky was married to Olga Fyodorovna Simkovitch in the Russian Empire.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] They were divorced and Olga remained in Russia with their daughter, Tania, as Sikorsky departed following the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1923, Sikorsky's sisters immigrated to the U.S., bringing six-year-old Tania with them.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky married Elisabeth Semion (1903–1995) in 1924, in New York.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky and Elisabeth had four sons; Sergei, Nikolai, Igor Jr. and George.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky died at his home in Easton, Connecticut, on October 26, 1972, and is buried in Saint John the Baptist Russian Orthodox Cemetery, located on Nichols Avenue in Stratford.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 1966, Sikorsky was inducted into the International Air & Space Hall of Fame.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky's and Andrei Tupolev's professional careers were covered in the 1979 Soviet biopic *The Poem of Wings* (Russian: Поэма о крыльях), where Sikorsky was portrayed by Yury Yakovlev.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] A working model of Sikorsky Ilya Muromets was recreated for filming.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The Sikorsky Memorial Bridge, which carries the Merritt Parkway across the Housatonic River next to the Sikorsky corporate headquarters, is named for him.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky has been designated a Connecticut Aviation Pioneer by the Connecticut State Legislature.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in Stratford, Connecticut, continues to the present day as one of the world's leading helicopter manufacturers, and a nearby small airport has been named Sikorsky Memorial Airport.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame and the Junior Achievement U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] 10090 Sikorsky, a main-belt asteroid discovered in 1990 at the Crimean Astrophysical Observatory, was named in honor of him.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In October 2011, one of the streets in Kyiv, Ukraine, was renamed for Sikorsky.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The decision was made by the City Council at the request of the U.S.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Embassy in Ukraine, which opened its new office on that street.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] The Sikorsky's family house in the city's historical center is preserved to this day but is in a neglected condition pending restoration.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In November 2012, one of the Russian supersonic heavy strategic bomber Tu-160, based at the Engels-2 Air Force Base, was named for Igor Sikorsky, which caused controversy among air base crew members.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] One of the officers said that Igor Sikorsky does not deserve it because he laid the foundations of the U.S., rather than Russian aviation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] However, the Long Range Aviation command officer said that Igor Sikorsky is not responsible for the activities of his military aircraft, noted that Sikorsky had also designed the first heavy bomber for Russia.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In 2013, *Flying* magazine ranked Sikorsky number 12 on its list of the 51 Heroes of Aviation.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] In August 2016, the National technical university of Ukraine "Kyiv politechnical institute" was named *National Technical University of Ukraine "Igor Sikorsky Kyiv Polytechnic Institute"* after its former student and outstanding aircraft designer.
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] On March 22, 2018, the Kyiv City Council officially renamed Kyiv International Airport to "Igor Sikorsky Kyiv International Airport Zhuliany".
[src:eugene-michael-gluhareff/igor-sikorsky] Sikorsky was a deeply religious Russian Orthodox Christian, and authored two religious and philosophical books (*The Message of the Lord's Prayer* and *The Invisible Encounter*).
